hing&rdquo;.</p>\r\n			</td>\r\n		</tr>\r\n		<tr>\r\n			<td style=\"width:576px\">\r\n			<p>&ldquo;People should study to have a perfect pronunciation&rdquo;.</p>\r\n			</td>\r\n		</tr>\r\n		<tr>\r\n			<td style=\"width:576px\">\r\n			<p>&ldquo;Language is a tool of communication&rdquo;.</p>\r\n			</td>\r\n		</tr>\r\n		<tr>\r\n			<td style=\"width:576px\">\r\n			<p>&ldquo;Teaching a foreign language is more than just being able to speak it well&rdquo;.</p>\r\n			</td>\r\n		</tr>\r\n	</tbody>\r\n</table>\r\n','RPT','S',0),(70,9,'Atividade 2: Expresse discordância e concordância','<table border=\"1\" cellpadding=\"0\" cellspacing=\"0\" style=\"width:576px\">\r\n	<tbody>\r\n		<tr>\r\n			<td style=\"width:576px\">\r\n			<p style=\"text-align:center\"><strong>Expressing disagreement</strong></p>\r\n			</td>\r\n		</tr>\r\n		<tr>\r\n			<td style=\"width:576px\">\r\n			<p>1. I&rsquo;m afraid I don&rsquo;t agree with what you said, because&hellip;</p>\r\n			</td>\r\n		</tr>\r\n		<tr>\r\n			<td style=\"width:576px\">\r\n			<p>2. I know the ideas mentioned by my colleagues are quite common, but I think that&hellip;</p>\r\n			</td>\r\n		</tr>\r\n		<tr>\r\n			<td style=\"width:576px\">\r\n			<p>3. I understand what my colleague said, but I have a different opinion on that.</p>\r\n			</td>\r\n		</tr>\r\n		<tr>\r\n			<td style=\"width:576px\">\r\n			<p>4. I think you are wrong!</p>\r\n			</td>\r\n		</tr>\r\n		<tr>\r\n			<td style=\"width:576px\">\r\n			<p>5. What are you talking about?</p>\r\n			</td>\r\n		</tr>\r\n		<tr>\r\n			<td style=\"width:576px\">\r\n			<p>6. I don&rsquo;t agree with you.</p>\r\n			</td>\r\n		</tr>\r\n	</tbody>\r\n</table>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<table border=\"1\" cellpadding=\"0\" cellspacing=\"0\" style=\"width:576px\">\r\n	<tbody>\r\n		<tr>\r\n			<td style=\"width:576px\">\r\n			<p style=\"text-align:center\"><strong>Expressing agreement</strong></p>\r\n			</td>\r\n		</tr>\r\n		<tr>\r\n			<td style=\"width:576px\">\r\n			<p>1. I think my colleague brought up a very important thing when she said that&hellip;</p>\r\n			</td>\r\n		</tr>\r\n		<tr>\r\n			<td style=\"width:576px\">\r\n			<p>2. I side with what they said because I also believe that&hellip;</p>\r\n			</td>\r\n		</tr>\r\n		<tr>\r\n			<td style=\"width:576px\">\r\n			<p>3. I couldn&rsquo;t agree more with your position.</p>\r\n			</td>\r\n		</tr>\r\n		<tr>\r\n			<td style=\"width:576px\">\r\n			<p>4. That&rsquo;s exactly how I think!</p>\r\n			</td>\r\n		</tr>\r\n	</tbody>\r\n</table>\r\n','RPT','S',0),(71,9,'Atividade 2: Discordância e Concordância','<table border=\"1\" cellpadding=\"0\" cellspacing=\"0\" style=\"width:576px\">\r\n	<tbody>\r\n		<tr>\r\n			<td style=\"width:576px\">\r\n			<p><strong>Expressing disagreement</strong></p>\r\n			</td>\r\n		</tr>\r\n		<tr>\r\n			<td style=\"width:576px\">\r\n			<p>1. I&rsquo;m afraid I don&rsquo;t agree with what you said, because&hellip;</p>\r\n			</td>\r\n		</tr>\r\n		<tr>\r\n			<td style=\"width:576px\">\r\n			<p>2. I know the ideas mentioned by my colleagues are quite common, but I think that&hellip;</p>\r\n			</td>\r\n		</tr>\r\n		<tr>\r\n			<td style=\"width:576px\">\r\n			<p>3. I understand what my colleague said, but I have a different opinion on that.</p>\r\n			</td>\r\n		</tr>\r\n		<tr>\r\n			<td style=\"width:576px\">\r\n			<p>4. I think you are wrong!</p>\r\n			</td>\r\n		</tr>\r\n		<tr>\r\n			<td style=\"width:576px\">\r\n			<p>5. What are you talking about?</p>\r\n			</td>\r\n		</tr>\r\n		<tr>\r\n			<td style=\"width:576px\">\r\n			<p>6. I don&rsquo;t agree with you.</p>\r\n			</td>\r\n		</tr>\r\n	</tbody>\r\n</table>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<table border=\"1\" cellpadding=\"0\" cellspacing=\"0\" style=\"width:576px\">\r\n	<tbody>\r\n		<tr>\r\n			<td style=\"width:576px\">\r\n			<p><strong>Expressing agreement</strong></p>\r\n			</td>\r\n		</tr>\r\n		<tr>\r\n			<td style=\"width:576px\">\r\n			<p>1. I think my colleague brought up a very important thing when she said that&hellip;</p>\r\n			</td>\r\n		</tr>\r\n		<tr>\r\n			<td style=\"width:576px\">\r\n			<p>2. I side with what they said, because I also believe that&hellip;</p>\r\n			</td>\r\n		</tr>\r\n		<tr>\r\n			<td style=\"width:576px\">\r\n			<p>3. I couldn&rsquo;t agree more with your position.</p>\r\n			</td>\r\n		</tr>\r\n		<tr>\r\n			<td style=\"width:576px\">\r\n			<p>4. That&rsquo;s exactly how I think!</p>\r\n			</td>\r\n		</tr>\r\n	</tbody>\r\n</table>\r\n','RPT','S',0),(72,9,'Atividade 5: Pedindo esclarecimentos, mais explicações e verificando a compreensão','<table border=\"1\" cellpadding=\"0\" cellspacing=\"0\" style=\"width:576px\">\r\n	<tbody>\r\n		<tr>\r\n			<td style=\"width:576px\">\r\n			<p><strong>Asking for clarification, further explanation and checking understanding</strong></p>\r\n			</td>\r\n		</tr>\r\n		<tr>\r\n			<td style=\"width:576px\">\r\n			<p>1. I&rsquo;m sorry, but I think I didn&rsquo;t really catch what you said about&hellip; Could you please explain that again?</p>\r\n			</td>\r\n		</tr>\r\n		<tr>\r\n			<td style=\"width:576px\">\r\n			<p>2. Could you elaborate on the idea that&hellip;?</p>\r\n			</td>\r\n		</tr>\r\n		<tr>\r\n			<td style=\"width:576px\">\r\n			<p>3. Would you mind giving an example of what you said concerning&hellip;?</p>\r\n			</td>\r\n		</tr>\r\n		<tr>\r\n			<td style=\"width:576px\">\r\n			<p>4. I don&rsquo;t quite understand what you meant by&hellip;</p>\r\n			</td>\r\n		</tr>\r\n		<tr>\r\n			<td style=\"width:576px\">\r\n			<p>5. Am I right in thinking that&hellip;?</p>\r\n			</td>\r\n		</tr>\r\n		<tr>\r\n			<td style=\"width:576px\">\r\n			<p>6. I don&rsquo;t know with I followed what you said.</p>\r\n			</td>\r\n		</tr>\r\n		<tr>\r\n			<td style=\"width:576px\">\r\n			<p>7. I&rsquo;m sorry, but if I understood it/you correctly&hellip;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;</p>\r\n			</td>\r\n		</tr>\r\n		<tr>\r\n			<td style=\"width:576px\">\r\n			<p>8. I&rsquo;m a little bit confused about next class assignment&hellip;</p>\r\n			</td>\r\n		</tr>\r\n	</tbody>\r\n</table>\r\n','RPT','S',0),(73,9,'Atividade 2: (Im)possibilidades Enunciativas','<div>\r\n<p>A professora tenta contornar a situa&ccedil;&atilde;o um pouco embara&ccedil;osa causada pelo riso da colega, encorajando Priscila a continuar seu racioc&iacute;nio (<em>Well, but no problems&hellip; go on. What do you think this &lsquo;course&rsquo; is about?</em>). Todavia, o di&aacute;logo poderia ter sido um pouco diferente. A professora, e n&atilde;o uma colega, poderia ter corrigido Priscila.&nbsp; Imaginemos a seguinte situa&ccedil;&atilde;o:</p>\r\n\r\n<p><em>Priscila:&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; I&rsquo;m Priscila... I don&rsquo;t know this &lsquo;curse&rsquo;&hellip; &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; </em></p>\r\n\r\n<p><em>Professora:&nbsp;&nbsp; Oh, course not curse, ok?</em></p>\r\n\r\n<p><em>Priscila:&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; What? I said wrong?</em></p>\r\n\r\n<p><em>Professora: Yes, you said &lsquo;curse&rsquo; but the word is &lsquo;course&rsquo;. Curse is a completely different thing&hellip;</em></p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>1) Como voc&ecirc; se sentiria no lugar de Priscila?</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>2) Como voc&ecirc; entende o posicionamento da professora?​</strong></p>\r\n</div>\r\n','RPT','N',0),(74,9,'Atividade 3: O que é inteligibilidade? ','<div>\r\n<p>Observe a fala de Priscila no Quadro 7 (<em>ok&hellip; right. I can&rsquo;t speak&hellip; I understand more and read... Well&hellip; this course about methodology?</em>). Apesar de se mostrar com algumas inconsist&ecirc;ncias gramaticais, pode-se compreend&ecirc;-la no contexto em que &eacute; enunciada. Isso nos remete &agrave; discuss&atilde;o sobre o conceito de <strong>inteligibilidade</strong>.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Nesse &aacute;udio 1, a partir de uma situa&ccedil;&atilde;o relativamente simples, aponta para as rela&ccedil;&otilde;es de poder que constituem a tomada da palavra, fazendo com que esta jamais seja um ato neutro.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Ao dizer <em>I&rsquo;d like to know how we can have access to the texts </em>(&aacute;udio 2)<em>, </em>Juliana n&atilde;o est&aacute; interessada em uma mera informa&ccedil;&atilde;o. O que est&aacute; aqui em jogo, mais do que a referencialidade da linguagem, &eacute; a possibilidade, para os falantes, de produzirem certos dizeres e assumirem lugares (social, discursivo) perante o outro. Diante da sugest&atilde;o da professora para que os alunos adquirissem os livros a serem estudados na disciplina, Juliana se posiciona contrariando a expectativa da docente (<em>But do you know if they are available in the library? I guess they&rsquo;re a little bit expensive</em>) (&aacute;udio 3) e, confrontando, de certa forma, uma voz institucional.</p>\r\n</div>\r\n','MUL','N',0),(75,10,'Atividade 1: Escuta e repetição','<p>Escuta e repeti&ccedil;&atilde;o dos di&aacute;logos</p>\r\n','RPT','N',1),(76,10,'Atividade 2: Expressões Idiomáticas','<p>Observe algumas express&otilde;es idiom&aacute;ticas que podem ser usadas para substituir as ditas pelos personagens.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Felicity: Good idea,&nbsp;<strong>I&rsquo;m starving</strong>!</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"margin-left:54pt\">1)&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; I could eat a horse.</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"margin-left:54pt\">2)&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; I could murder a (burger /&nbsp;steak&nbsp;/ pizza) right now!</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"margin-left:54pt\">3)&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; I&rsquo;m so ravenous I could eat a horse!</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"margin-left:54pt\">4)&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; I&rsquo;m so starved I could eat a horse!</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"margin-left:54pt\">5)&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; I&rsquo;m famished. I could murder a burger!</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"margin-left:54pt\">6)&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; I&rsquo;m so hungry I could murder a whole pizza right now!</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Ethan:<strong> Are you crazy</strong>? Oh God!&nbsp;<strong>You eat a lot</strong>.</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"margin-left:54pt\">1)&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Have you ever gone bananas? You eat like a horse.</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"margin-left:54pt\">2)&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Have you ever gone bananas? You eat like a pig.</p>\r\n','PRC','N',2),(77,10,'XAtividade 3: Praticando os modais','<p>Escolha o melhor sentido para esses verbos modais.</p>\r\n','MUL','S',0),(78,10,'Atividade 3: The food song','<p>Observe as figuras com comidas e coisas relacionadas &agrave; comida que se encontram na can&ccedil;&atilde;o: <strong>The Food Song</strong> de Barbra Lica.</p>\r\n','MUL','S',0),(79,10,'Atividade 4: The food song (letra e vídeo)','<p>The Food Song<br />\r\nBy Barbra Lica</p>\r\n\r\n<p><br />\r\nHey, I had a bad day,</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>And I wondered how it <strong>TASTES</strong>,</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>So I ATE...</p>\r\n\r\n<p>And then I served myself a second <strong>PLATE</strong>.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Hey, I had a bad week,</p>\r\n\r\n<p>And I wonder if it&#39;s <strong>SWEET</strong>,</p>\r\n\r\n<p>So I&#39;ll <strong>EAT</strong>...</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&#39;Cause I deserve to give myself a treat...</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Sadness tastes like <strong>FRENCH FRIES</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p>And anger tastes like <strong>WINE</strong>...</p>\r\n\r\n<p>They&#39;re only <strong>GRAPES </strong>but give them time.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Hey, I had a bad night,</p>\r\n\r\n<p>So I wrapped it up in <strong>PIE</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p>And let it <strong>BAKE</strong>...</p>\r\n\r\n<p>So all my feelings taste like <strong>TENDERFLAKE</strong>.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Oh joy, my mum just called.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>And she&#39;s appalled because my dad don&#39;t want to <strong>SPOON</strong>,</p>\r\n\r\n<p>I&#39;ll take that <strong>SPOON</strong>, and put some <strong>ICE-CREAM </strong>on my afternoon.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>But guilty tastes like <strong>NOODLES</strong>.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Lonely tastes like <strong>BREAD</strong>.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>But <strong>TOAST </strong>can make a royal friend, hmmm!</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Yup! Everything is wonderful...</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Yeah! So walk it off, walk it off,</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Circle the block,</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The <strong>COOKIES </strong>and <strong>CREAM</strong> are starting to talk to me...</p>\r\n\r\n<p>I&#39;m just crazy...</p>\r\n\r\n<p>But crazy tastes so good,</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Crazy tastes so nice.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Crazy tastes like never-have-to-go outside.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Here we go now!</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Hey, I had a bad day so I ate it all.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Hey, I had a bad day and <strong>I&#39;M STUFFED.</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p>Hey, I had a bad day and <strong>I&#39;M STUFFED</strong>.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Hey, I had a bad day and <strong>I&#39;M STUFFED</strong>.</p>\r\n','MUL','N',4),(80,10,'Atividade 5: The food song (Karaoke)','<p>Vamos cantar! Ou&ccedil;a e repita!</p>\r\n','RPT','N',5),(81,10,'XAtividade 7: Combinar as frases','<p>Combine a express&atilde;o idiom&aacute;tica com o seu significado.</p>\r\n\r\n<ol>\r\n	<li>(&nbsp; ) Your eyes are bigger than your stomach</li>\r\n	<li>(&nbsp; ) Have you ever gone bananas?</li>\r\n	<li>(&nbsp; ) Compare apples to oranges</li>\r\n	<li>(&nbsp; ) Eat like a horse</li>\r\n	<li>(&nbsp; ) Cry over spilled milk</li>\r\n	<li>(&nbsp; ) Piece of cake</li>\r\n	<li>(&nbsp; ) Bring home the bacon</li>\r\n	<li>(&nbsp; ) Have egg on one&rsquo;s face</li>\r\n	<li>(&nbsp; ) I ate like a pig</li>\r\n	<li>(&nbsp; ) A rotten apple</li>\r\n	<li>(&nbsp; ) A smart cookie</li>\r\n	<li>(&nbsp; ) As busy as popcorn on a skillet</li>\r\n	<li>(&nbsp; ) Back to the salt mines</li>\r\n	<li>(&nbsp; ) Big cheese</li>\r\n	<li>(&nbsp; ) Bite the hand that feeds one</li>\r\n	<li>(&nbsp; ) I&rsquo;m cheesed off</li>\r\n	<li>(&nbsp; ) Couch potato</li>\r\n	<li>(&nbsp; ) As cool as a cucumber</li>\r\n	<li>(&nbsp; ) Fruits of one&rsquo;s labor</li>\r\n	<li>(&nbsp; ) Hot potato</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n','MUL','S',0),(82,10,'Atividade 8: Entonação','<table border=\"1\" cellpadding=\"0\" cellspacing=\"0\" style=\"width:576px\">\r\n	<tbody>\r\n		<tr>\r\n			<td style=\"width:288px\">\r\n			<p>Exerc&iacute;cio sobre entona&ccedil;&otilde;es</p>\r\n			</td>\r\n			<td style=\"width:288px\">\r\n			<p>Exerc&iacute;cio sobre polidez</p>\r\n			</td>\r\n		</tr>\r\n		<tr>\r\n			<td style=\"width:288px\">\r\n			<p>Falas e express&otilde;es faciais com diferentes entona&ccedil;&otilde;es e efeitos de sentido:</p>\r\n\r\n			<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n			<p>I have a reservation for&hellip;</p>\r\n\r\n			<p>I want my steak well done.</p>\r\n\r\n			<p>I want my steak medium.</p>\r\n\r\n			<p>I want my steak rare.</p>\r\n\r\n			<p>I ordered sparkling water.</p>\r\n\r\n			<p>I ordered still water.</p>\r\n\r\n			<p>I&rsquo;ll be right back.</p>\r\n\r\n			<p>Enjoy your meal!</p>\r\n\r\n			<p>There&rsquo;s a mistake on the bill</p>\r\n\r\n			<p>I need to go to the hospital.</p>\r\n\r\n			<p>I feel sick.</p>\r\n\r\n			<p>I need to see a doctor immediately!</p>\r\n\r\n			<p>Call an ambulance!</p>\r\n\r\n			<p>It hurts here.</p>\r\n\r\n			<p>I have a fever.</p>\r\n\r\n			<p>I have a cold.</p>\r\n\r\n			<p>I have a cough.</p>\r\n\r\n			<p>I feel dizzy.</p>\r\n\r\n			<p>I don&#39;t have any appetite.</p>\r\n\r\n			<p>I think that I have eaten something bad.</p>\r\n\r\n			<p>I&#39;m pregnant.</p>\r\n\r\n			<p>Is it contagious?</p>\r\n\r\n			<p>Here are my insurance documents.</p>\r\n\r\n			<p>I don&#39;t have health insurance.</p>\r\n\r\n			<p>I&#39;m allergic to&hellip;<br />\r\n			&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n			<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n			</td>\r\n			<td style=\"width:288px\">\r\n			<p>Exemplos de perguntas e respostas:</p>\r\n\r\n			<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n			<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n			<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n			<p>Could you bring me the menu, please?</p>\r\n\r\n			<p>I&rsquo;d like to order.</p>\r\n\r\n			<p>May I take your order?</p>\r\n\r\n			<p>What would you like to eat?</p>\r\n\r\n			<p>What do you recommend?</p>\r\n\r\n			<p>Can you bring me a fork, please?</p>\r\n\r\n			<p>Can you bring me a spoon, please? Can you bring me a knife, please?</p>\r\n\r\n			<p>It was excellent! Can I have the check/bill, please?</p>\r\n\r\n			<p>Could you bring me some ice, please?</p>\r\n\r\n			<p>Could you bring me a napkin, please?</p>\r\n\r\n			<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n			</td>\r\n		</tr>\r\n	</tbody>\r\n</table>\r\n','PRN','S',0),(83,10,'Atividade 6: Leitura e compreensão do texto','<p style=\"margin-left:36pt\">Leia e responda as quest&otilde;es!</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:24px\"><strong>Our Moods, Our Foods</strong></span><br />\r\n<span style=\"font-size:18px\">The messy relationship between how we feel and what we eat</span></p>\r\n\r\n<div class=\"c-article-meta\" style=\"box-sizing: inherit; -webkit-box-align: baseline; align-items: baseline; display: flex; flex-wrap: wrap; color: rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family: AGaramondPro, \">\r\n<address>\r\n<address><span style=\"font-size:14px\"><a class=\"c-byline__link\" href=\"https://www.theatlantic.com/author/julie-beck/\" style=\"background-color: transparent; color: rgb(231, 19, 26); text-decoration-line: none; transition: all 0.15s ease 0s; box-sizing: inherit;\">JULIE BECK</a>&nbsp;</span><span style=\"font-size:10px\">MARCH 6, 2014</span></address>\r\n</address>\r\n</div>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:16px\"><span style=\"font-family:lucida sans unicode,lucida grande,sans-serif\"><span style=\"color:rgb(0, 0, 0)\">Eating a meal, any meal, reliably makes an animal, any animal, calmer and more lethargic. This means humans, too. Hunger makes animals alert and irritable, which explains why couples always fight about where to eat dinner. This emotional response encourages the animals to find food.</span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<div class=\"ad-boxinjector-m-wrapper\" style=\"box-sizing: inherit; margin-bottom: 16px; margin-top: 0px; color: rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family: AGaramondPro, \">\r\n<div class=\"ad-boxinjector-m-wrapper\" style=\"box-sizing: inherit; margin-bottom: 16px; margin-top: 0px; color: rgb(0, 0, 0); text-align: justify;\"><span style=\"font-size:16px\"><span style=\"font-family:lucida sans unicode,lucida grande,sans-serif\">But all this is only in the broadest, most primal &ldquo;eating = good, not eating = bad&rdquo; way. The details of the relationship between foods and moods end up being a little contradictory and a lot complicated.</span></span></div>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:16px\"><span style=\"font-family:lucida sans unicode,lucida grande,sans-serif\">What we tend to think of as &ldquo;emotional eating&rdquo; is a specific kind of eating and a specific kind of emotion&mdash;eating sugary, fatty, carb-y, unhealthy foods as a coping mechanism for feeling upset. &nbsp;In reality, &ldquo;emotional eating&rdquo; is a much broader term.</span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:16px\"><span style=\"font-family:lucida sans unicode,lucida grande,sans-serif\">&ldquo;We eat for a variety of different emotions and we eat in a variety of different circumstances which are in turn connected with emotions,&rdquo; Meryl Gardner, a marketing professor at the University of Delaware, says.</span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:16px\"><span style=\"font-family:lucida sans unicode,lucida grande,sans-serif\">Gardner was the lead author on a&nbsp;<a href=\"http://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/S1057740814000060\" style=\"background-color: transparent; color: rgb(0, 0, 0); transition: all 0.15s ease 0s; box-sizing: inherit; font-size: 0.99em;\">new study</a>&nbsp;published in the&nbsp;<em>Journal of Consumer Psychology,&nbsp;</em>which looked at food choice and mood, adding to a fairly extensive body of research that already exists on the interplay between moods and foods.</span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<div class=\"ad-boxinjector-m-wrapper\" style=\"box-sizing: inherit; margin-bottom: 16px; margin-top: 0px; color: rgb(0, 0, 0); text-align: justify;\"><span style=\"font-size:16px\"><span style=\"font-family:lucida sans unicode,lucida grande,sans-serif\">There seems to be a clear, fairly consistent connection between negative emotions and unhealthy foods, though there are individual variations for what&nbsp;<em>kind</em>&nbsp;of snack people want. In a bad mood, people&rsquo;s hands tend to float to the cookie jar, the candy bag, the snack drawer. What&rsquo;s less clear is what foods we&rsquo;re drawn to in a positive mood.</span></span></div>\r\n</div>\r\n\r\n<div class=\"ad-boxinjector-m-wrapper\" style=\"box-sizing: inherit; margin-bottom: 16px; margin-top: 0px; color: rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family: AGaramondPro, \">\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:16px\"><span style=\"font-family:lucida sans unicode,lucida grande,sans-serif\">What we tend to think of as &ldquo;emotional eating&rdquo; is a specific kind of eating and a specific kind of emotion&mdash;eating sugary, fatty, carb-y, unhealthy foods as a coping mechanism for feeling upset. &nbsp;In reality, &ldquo;emotional eating&rdquo; is a much broader term.</span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:16px\"><span style=\"font-family:lucida sans unicode,lucida grande,sans-serif\">&ldquo;We eat for a variety of different emotions and we eat in a variety of different circumstances which are in turn connected with emotions,&rdquo; Meryl Gardner, a marketing professor at the University of Delaware, says.</span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:16px\"><span style=\"font-family:lucida sans unicode,lucida grande,sans-serif\">Gardner was the lead author on a&nbsp;<a href=\"http://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/S1057740814000060\" style=\"background-color: transparent; color: rgb(0, 0, 0); transition: all 0.15s ease 0s; box-sizing: inherit; font-size: 0.99em;\">new study</a>&nbsp;published in the&nbsp;<em>Journal of Consumer Psychology,&nbsp;</em>which looked at food choice and mood, adding to a fairly extensive body of research that already exists on the interplay between moods and foods.</span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<div class=\"ad-boxinjector-m-wrapper\" style=\"box-sizing: inherit; margin-bottom: 16px; margin-top: 0px; color: rgb(0, 0, 0); text-align: justify;\"><span style=\"font-size:16px\"><span style=\"font-family:lucida sans unicode,lucida grande,sans-serif\">There seems to be a clear, fairly consistent connection between negative emotions and unhealthy foods, though there are individual variations for what&nbsp;<em>kind</em>&nbsp;of snack people want. In a bad mood, people&rsquo;s hands tend to float to the cookie jar, the candy bag, the snack drawer. What&rsquo;s less clear is what foods we&rsquo;re drawn to in a positive mood.</span></span></div>\r\n</div>\r\n\r\n<div class=\"ad-boxinjector-m-wrapper\" style=\"box-sizing: inherit; margin-bottom: 16px; margin-top: 0px; color: rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family: AGaramondPro, \">\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:16px\"><span style=\"font-family:lucida sans unicode,lucida grande,sans-serif\">Some studies say we still want treats. A&nbsp;<a href=\"http://psycnet.apa.org/?&amp;fa=main.doiLanding&amp;doi=10.1037/0021-843X.101.2.348\" style=\"background-color: transparent; color: rgb(0, 0, 0); transition: all 0.15s ease 0s; box-sizing: inherit; font-size: 0.99em;\">1992 study</a>&nbsp;and a&nbsp;<a href=\"http://ac.els-cdn.com/S019566630290499X/1-s2.0-S019566630290499X-main.pdf?_tid=edbdeba6-a479-11e3-a8a5-00000aacb360&amp;acdnat=1394033113_c88ed7a56c3e1767060124c3588f4ec2\" style=\"background-color: transparent; color: rgb(0, 0, 0); transition: all 0.15s ease 0s; box-sizing: inherit; font-size: 0.99em;\">2002 study</a>&nbsp;(one on women, one on men) found that joy led to increased consumption of indulgent foods. A 2013 study in&nbsp;<em>Appetite</em>&nbsp;titled &ldquo;<a href=\"http://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/S019566631300130X\" style=\"background-color: transparent; color: rgb(0, 0, 0); transition: all 0.15s ease 0s; box-sizing: inherit; font-size: 0.99em;\">Happy Eating: The underestimated role of overeating in a positive mood</a>&rdquo; points out the potential for increased consumption (in this case of chips and chocolate) when we&rsquo;re feeling good.</span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:16px\"><span style=\"font-family:lucida sans unicode,lucida grande,sans-serif\">Other research says just the opposite&mdash;that we&rsquo;re more likely to eschew the sugar/carb rush when happy. In 2010,&nbsp;<a href=\"http://www.jstor.org/discover/10.1086/655665?uid=3739256&amp;uid=2&amp;uid=4&amp;sid=21103592979347\" style=\"background-color: transparent; color: rgb(0, 0, 0); transition: all 0.15s ease 0s; box-sizing: inherit; font-size: 0.99em;\">researchers found</a>&nbsp;that people in a positive mood were more likely to choose grapes over chocolate than those in a neutral mood.&nbsp;<a href=\"http://www.jstor.org/discover/10.1086/597159?uid=3739256&amp;uid=2&amp;uid=4&amp;sid=21103592979347\" style=\"background-color: transparent; color: rgb(0, 0, 0); transition: all 0.15s ease 0s; box-sizing: inherit; font-size: 0.99em;\">Another study</a>&nbsp;offers a qualification, finding that people would choose healthy foods if they felt like their good mood was going to stick around; if not, they might eat more indulgent foods, to keep the good vibes going.</span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<div class=\"ad-boxinjector-m-wrapper\" style=\"box-sizing: inherit; margin-bottom: 16px; margin-top: 0px; color: rgb(0, 0, 0); text-align: justify;\"><span style=\"font-size:16px\"><span style=\"font-family:lucida sans unicode,lucida grande,sans-serif\">Gardner&rsquo;s study also found a connection between negative moods and unhealthy foods, and positive moods and healthy foods, but she and her team introduced the element of time into the equation as well. They had participants think about either the present or the future (by describing their current residence, or a possible future residence). They found that regardless of mood, long-term, future-focused thinking led to healthier choices.</span></span></div>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:16px\"><span style=\"font-family:lucida sans unicode,lucida grande,sans-serif\">&ldquo;When you&rsquo;re in a good mood, you take a longer-term perspective,&rdquo; Gardner says. &ldquo;You see the forest, not the trees... When you&rsquo;re focused on the near term, when you&rsquo;re looking at what&rsquo;s in front of your nose, you respond with what&rsquo;s going to give you quick pleasure. And that&rsquo;s triggered very much by bad moods. But we can fight that.&rdquo;</span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:16px\"><span style=\"font-family:lucida sans unicode,lucida grande,sans-serif\">Dr. Leigh Gibson, a psychology professor at the University of Roehampton in London, disagrees, though he says he finds those results interesting. &ldquo;I&rsquo;m not sure that&rsquo;s the way people normally go about their daily eating,&rdquo; he says. &ldquo;For habitual behaviors like eating, there tends to be an intention-behavior gap. We have all these wonderful intentions, but when it comes down to it, we&rsquo;re exposed to energy-dense foods when we find ourselves hungry.&rdquo;</span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<div class=\"ad-boxinjector-m-wrapper\" style=\"box-sizing: inherit; margin-bottom: 16px; margin-top: 0px; color: rgb(0, 0, 0); text-align: justify;\"><span style=\"font-size:16px\"><span style=\"font-family:lucida sans unicode,lucida grande,sans-serif\">It does seem unlikely that most of us would take the time to describe our future homes to ourselves before deciding on pizza or a salad for lunch. And as previously noted, there is little consensus on what we typically crave when we&rsquo;re happy.</span></span></div>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:16px\"><span style=\"font-family:lucida sans unicode,lucida grande,sans-serif\">Part of the reason why it seems our moods rarely drive us toward healthy foods, Gibson says, is that for much of human history, energy-dense foods, or what we now consider comfort foods, were the ideal thing to eat.</span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:16px\"><span style=\"font-family:lucida sans unicode,lucida grande,sans-serif\">&ldquo;We didn&rsquo;t evolve as homo sapiens by eating healthy, because all we had to do was reproduce and survive until our mid-20&rsquo;s,&rdquo; he says. &ldquo;We were quite happily sucking the marrow out of bones. We were just getting energy, protein, the basic nutrients we needed, but we didn&rsquo;t have to live too long. Healthy eating is a modern, cultural thing that we now need, because we&rsquo;re living so long&hellip; You could almost say the default is comfort eating.&rdquo;</span></span></p>\r\n</div>\r\n\r\n<div class=\"ad-boxinjector-m-wrapper\" style=\"box-sizing: inherit; margin-bottom: 16px; margin-top: 0px; color: rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family: AGaramondPro, \">\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:16px\"><span style=\"font-family:lucida sans unicode,lucida grande,sans-serif\">We&rsquo;re not constantly shoveling mashed potatoes into our mouths (at least not most of the time), so of course this doesn&rsquo;t mean that humans don&rsquo;t ever choose healthy foods, just that when we do, it might not be in response to our emotions.</span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<div class=\"ad-boxinjector-m-wrapper\" style=\"box-sizing: inherit; margin-bottom: 16px; margin-top: 0px; color: rgb(0, 0, 0); text-align: justify;\"><span style=\"font-size:16px\"><span style=\"font-family:lucida sans unicode,lucida grande,sans-serif\">Another reason for this lack of consensus is that there are a variety of moods that can fit under the &ldquo;positive&rdquo; umbrella&mdash;feeling excited is very different from feeling content, and those emotions could lead to similarly divergent food choices.</span></span></div>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:16px\"><span style=\"font-family:lucida sans unicode,lucida grande,sans-serif\">For example, Gardner says we tend to go for special, often unhealthy, foods on celebratory occasions, like birthdays or Thanksgiving.</span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:16px\"><span style=\"font-family:lucida sans unicode,lucida grande,sans-serif\">&ldquo;You eat the birthday cake, you may go out in the evening and eat more appetizers and drink more cocktails than you intended, and it&rsquo;s all part of the specialness of the occasion,&rdquo; she says. &ldquo;And we&rsquo;ve all learned to celebrate with food. It&rsquo;s part of so many different cultures.&rdquo;</span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:16px\"><span style=\"font-family:lucida sans unicode,lucida grande,sans-serif\">Carol Landau&mdash;a clinical professor of psychiatry, human behavior, and medicine at Brown University&mdash;points out that some comfort eaters turn everything into a celebration, rewarding themselves with food not just for special occasions, but for everyday accomplishments as well.</span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:16px\"><span style=\"font-family:lucida sans unicode,lucida grande,sans-serif\">&ldquo;Food is such an important part of culture,&rdquo; Landau says. &ldquo;I think we&rsquo;re asking people to do a lot [by asking them] to avoid comfort eating.&rdquo;</span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<div class=\"ad-boxinjector-m-wrapper\" style=\"box-sizing: inherit; margin-bottom: 16px; margin-top: 0px; color: rgb(0, 0, 0); text-align: justify;\"><span style=\"font-size:16px\"><span style=\"font-family:lucida sans unicode,lucida grande,sans-serif\">Gibson says this sort of celebratory eating seems to be more prevalent for men than women. There&rsquo;s also some evidence that the foods men and women turn to for comfort are different&mdash;men often get more comfort from savory foods and &ldquo;general meal-type foods,&rdquo; Gibson says, as opposed to snacks. Gardner says she has also found men to be more drawn to salty foods.</span></span></div>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:16px\"><span style=\"font-family:lucida sans unicode,lucida grande,sans-serif\">Sweet foods, however, seem to be a universal crowd-pleaser.</span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:16px\"><span style=\"font-family:lucida sans unicode,lucida grande,sans-serif\">&ldquo;Sweetness is such a powerful stimulus,&rdquo; Gibson says. &ldquo;We&rsquo;re born initially liking sweetness. It probably helps [that babies] have an appetite for breast milk and so on.&rdquo;</span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:16px\"><span style=\"font-family:lucida sans unicode,lucida grande,sans-serif\">This may well be why the go-to image of comfort eating in culture is someone crying into a pint of Ben &amp; Jerry&rsquo;s, and why so many studies on mood and food choice include chocolate as one of the unhealthy options.</span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:16px\"><span style=\"font-family:lucida sans unicode,lucida grande,sans-serif\">&ldquo;If one can characterize [comfort] foods in any simple way, it would be that they&rsquo;re typically energy-dense,&rdquo; Gibson says. &ldquo;Therefore they&rsquo;re probably high fat, and they might be sweet as well. The perfect comfort food might be chocolate.&rdquo;</span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<div class=\"ad-boxinjector-m-wrapper\" style=\"box-sizing: inherit; margin-bottom: 16px; margin-top: 0px; color: rgb(0, 0, 0); text-align: justify;\"><span style=\"font-size:16px\"><span style=\"font-family:lucida sans unicode,lucida grande,sans-serif\">But as we all know, the positive effects of eating sweets are short-lived. Whether it&rsquo;s a crash that comes after a sugar high, or just a feeling of guilt after eating more cookies than you planned, treats are not a ticket to long-term happiness.</span></span></div>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:16px\"><span style=\"font-family:lucida sans unicode,lucida grande,sans-serif\">So in the chicken-or-the-egg problem of food and mood, do the moods hatch the foods, or do the foods hatch the moods? Studies disagree&mdash;the relationship seems to go both ways. A couple recent studies suggest that the foods come first.</span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:16px\"><span style=\"font-family:lucida sans unicode,lucida grande,sans-serif\">In a&nbsp;<a href=\"http://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/S019566631100643X\" style=\"background-color: transparent; color: rgb(0, 0, 0); transition: all 0.15s ease 0s; box-sizing: inherit; font-size: 0.99em;\">study published in 2012</a>, Penn State psychology professor Dr. Helen Hendy had 44 undergraduate students keep week-long diaries of how they felt and what they ate. She analyzed the results in terms of four things the Centers for Disease Control and Prevention recommend we should limit to improve physical health: calories, carbohydrates, saturated fat, and sodium. Following those recommendations, Hendy found, seemed to have benefits for improving moods as well.</span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:16px\"><span style=\"font-family:lucida sans unicode,lucida grande,sans-serif\">She found that the link between foods and moods played out over a period of two days&mdash;what you ate on day one was linked to how you felt on day three, etc. As usual, the correlation was more consistent with negative moods: &ldquo;Consumption of calories, saturated fat, and sodium was significantly associated with increased negative mood two days later,&rdquo; the study reads.</span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<div class=\"ad-boxinjector-m-wrapper\" style=\"box-sizing: inherit; margin-bottom: 16px; margin-top: 0px; color: rgb(0, 0, 0); text-align: justify;\"><span style=\"font-size:16px\"><span style=\"font-family:lucida sans unicode,lucida grande,sans-serif\">&ldquo;Some of my research leads me to change my habits, and this one has,&rdquo; Hendy says. &ldquo;I have a big meeting [in two days], so today I&rsquo;m going to watch my calories, my sodium, and my saturated fat, so I can hopefully have a chance to be in a good mood.&rdquo;</span></span></div>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:16px\"><span style=\"font-family:lucida sans unicode,lucida grande,sans-serif\">A similar study,&nbsp;<a href=\"http://onlinelibrary.wiley.com/doi/10.1111/bjhp.12021/abstract\" style=\"background-color: transparent; color: rgb(0, 0, 0); transition: all 0.15s ease 0s; box-sizing: inherit; font-size: 0.99em;\">published in the&nbsp;<em>British Journal of Health Psychology</em></a>&nbsp;in 2013, had 281 undergrads keep a 21-day diary, and did find a correlation between eating fruits and vegetables one day and being in a positive mood the next day. The association with eating fruit was stronger for men, but both men and women benefitted from eating veggies. Participants&rsquo; BMI did not affect the association.</span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:16px\"><span style=\"font-family:lucida sans unicode,lucida grande,sans-serif\">The exact reasons why healthy eating might make you happy are unclear, but Gibson posits that if you intend to eat healthily, and you follow through, that could put you in a good mood. &ldquo;Achieving goals is part and parcel of emotional experience,&rdquo; he says.</span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:16px\"><span style=\"font-family:lucida sans unicode,lucida grande,sans-serif\">Both eating and emotion are such regular, consistent parts of our lives that it&rsquo;s inevitable they would get tangled up together. Unfortunately, though research has illuminated some interesting possibilities as to how they relate to one another, the knot is still very much intact and it&rsquo;s hard to see where one ends and the other begins.</span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:16px\"><span style=\"font-family:lucida sans unicode,lucida grande,sans-serif\">&ldquo;There&rsquo;s not a very neat story there,&rdquo; Gibson says. Regardless, there&rsquo;s a bit more to it than just feeling sad and therefore reaching for a spoon and some ice cream, or whatever your preferred unhealthy snack is. It seems entirely possible that all eating is, in fact, emotional eating.&nbsp;</span></span></p>\r\n</div>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"margin-left:36pt\"><strong>Source</strong>:&nbsp;<a href=\"https://www.theatlantic.com/health/archive/2014/03/our-moods-our-foods/284238/\">https://www.theatlantic.com/health/archive/2014/03/our-moods-our-foods/284238/</a></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"margin-left:54pt\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"margin-left:54pt\"><span style=\"font-size:18px\">1)&nbsp; According to the text what are the emotions linked to the necessity of eating?</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"margin-left:54pt\"><span style=\"font-size:18px\">2)&nbsp;&nbsp; In the song,&nbsp;<strong>The Food Song</strong>, what are the reasons that lead the protagonist to eat?</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"margin-left:54pt\"><span style=\"font-size:18px\">3)&nbsp;&nbsp; And you, what are the emotions that affect your diet? Explain: What are your food choices in different situations?</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"margin-left:36pt\"><span style=\"font-size:18px\">&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;4)&nbsp;&nbsp; Are you an emotional eater? Why?</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"margin-left:36pt\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"margin-left:36pt\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n','RPT','N',6),(84,11,'Atividade 1: Partes do corpo','<p>Observe as partes do corpo.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n','MUL','N',0),(85,11,'Atividade 2: Complete com as partes do corpo','<p><img alt=\"\" src=\"https://labvirtual.ileel.ufu.br/lab/upload/filemanager/uploads/BODY%201.JPG\" style=\"height:523px; width:594px\" /></p>\r\n\r\n<p><img alt=\"\" src=\"https://labvirtual.ileel.ufu.br/lab/upload/filemanager/uploads/HEAD%202.JPG\" style=\"height:520px; width:606px\" /></p>\r\n','MUL','N',0),(86,11,'Atividade 3: Vamos praticar!','<p>Digite a resposta correta nos espa&ccedil;os em branco: must - can&#39;t - might</p>\r\n','MUL','N',0),(87,11,'Atividade 4: Sobre racismo','<p style=\"margin-left:18pt\">One of the social issues addressed by the story is that of racism. As it is well known, racism consists in the belief of a supposed supremacy of one race over another. Although there are various campaigns to combat racism in different parts of the world, this is a practice that still manifests itself in different ways in our daily lives. Could you tell us how these practices materialize in the story presented? Why does it happen?</p>\r\n','RPT','N',0),(88,11,'Atividade 5: Leia o texto','<p style=\"margin-left:18pt\">As mentioned before, racist practices manifest themselves in different ways, one of which is in the strangeness of certain languages&nbsp;and / or&nbsp;linguistic practices. In the English language, some of their speakers suffer from racism simply because they speak differently from what is considered standard English. Have you ever heard about African English? How Let&rsquo;s learn a little about this variant?</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"margin-left:18pt\"><strong>Read the text and answer the following questions.</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"margin-left:18pt\">What is Ebonics (African American English)?</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"margin-left:90pt\">By John R. Rickford</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"margin-left:18pt\">At its most literal level, Ebonics simply means &#39;black speech&#39; (a blend of the words ebony &#39;black&#39; and phonics &#39;sounds&#39;). The term was created in 1973 by a group of black scholars who disliked the negative connotations of terms like &#39;Nonstandard Negro English&#39; that had been coined in the 1960s when the first modern large-scale linguistic studies of African American speech-communities began. However, the term Ebonics never caught on among linguists, much less among the general public. That all changed with the &#39;Ebonics&#39; controversy of December 1996 when the Oakland (CA) School Board recognized it as the &#39;primary&#39; language of its majority African American students and resolved to take it into account in teaching them standard or academic English.</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"margin-left:18pt\">1____________________________________________</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"margin-left:18pt\">Ebonics pronunciation includes features like the omission of the final consonant in words like &#39;past&#39; (pas&#39; ) and &#39;hand&#39; (han&#39;), the pronunciation of the&nbsp;th in&nbsp;&#39;bath&#39; as t (bat) or f (baf), and the pronunciation of the vowel in words like &#39;my&#39; and &#39;ride&#39; as a long ah (mah,&nbsp;rahd). Some of these occur in vernacular white English, too, especially in the South, but in&nbsp;general&nbsp;they occur more frequently in Ebonics. Some Ebonics pronunciations are more unique, for instance, dropping b, d,&nbsp;or g&nbsp;at the beginning of auxiliary verbs like &#39;don&#39;t&#39; and &#39;gonna&#39;, yielding Ah &#39;on know for &quot;I don&#39;t know&quot; and ama do it for &quot;I&#39;m going to do it.&quot;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"margin-left:18pt\">2____________________________________________</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"margin-left:18pt\">These distinctive Ebonics pronunciations are all systematic, the result of regular rules and restrictions; they are not random &#39;error&#39;--and this is equally true of Ebonics grammar. For instance, Ebonics speakers regularly produce sentences without present tense is and are, as in &quot;John&nbsp;trippin&quot; or &quot;They&nbsp;allright&quot;. But they don&#39;t omit present tense am. Instead of the ungrammatical *&quot;Ah&nbsp;walkin&quot;, Ebonics speakers would say *&quot;Ahm&nbsp;walkin.&quot; Likewise, they do not omit is and are if they come at the end of a sentence--&quot;That&#39;s what he/they&quot; is ungrammatical. Many members of the public seem to have heard, too, that Ebonics speakers use an &#39;invariant&#39; be in their speech (as in &quot;They be&nbsp;goin&nbsp;to school every day&quot;); however, this&nbsp;be&nbsp;is not simply equivalent to is or are. Invariant&nbsp;be refers&nbsp;to actions that occur regularly or habitually rather than on just one occasion.</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"margin-left:18pt\">3____________________________________________</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"margin-left:18pt\">That depends on whom you ask. Black writers from Paul Laurence Dunbar to Zora Neale Hurston to August Wilson have made extensive use of it in their work, and some, like James Baldwin (&quot;this passion, this skill, ... this incredible music.&quot;), Toni Morrison, and June Jordan have praised it explicitly. Black preachers and comedians and singers, especially rappers, also use it for&nbsp;dramatic&nbsp;or realistic effect. But many other people, black and white, regard it as a sign of limited education or sophistication, as a legacy of slavery or an impediment to socioeconomic mobility. Some deny its existence (like the black Chicagoan whose words &quot;Ain&#39;t nobody here talkin&#39; no Ebonics&quot; belied his claim). Others deprecate it (like Maya Angelou, who found the Oakland School Board&#39;s 1996 Ebonics resolutions &quot;very threatening&quot; although she uses Ebonics herself in her poems, e.g. &quot;The Pusher&quot;).</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"margin-left:18pt\">4____________________________________________</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"margin-left:18pt\">On this point, linguists are quite divided. Some emphasize its English origins, pointing to the fact that most of the vocabulary of Ebonics is from English and that much of its pronunciation (e.g. pronouncing final&nbsp;th&nbsp;as f) and grammar (e.g. double negatives, &quot;I don&#39;t want none&quot;) could have come from the nonstandard dialects of English indentured servants and other workers with whom African slaves interacted. Others emphasize Ebonics&#39; African origins, noting that West African languages often lack&nbsp;th&nbsp;sounds and final consonant clusters (e.g. past),&nbsp;and that replacing or simplifying these occurs both in US Ebonics and in West African English varieties spoken in Nigeria and Ghana.</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"margin-left:18pt\">(Adapted&nbsp;from:&nbsp;https://www.linguisticsociety.org/content/what-ebonics-african-american-english )</p>\r\n','MUL','N',0),(89,13,'Atividade 1: Escuta e repetição','<p>Escute&nbsp;e repita&nbsp;os di&aacute;logos.</p>\r\n','RPT','N',0),(90,13,'XAtividade 2','<p>Com quadrinhos: O que mais podemos dizer para completar os bal&otilde;es?</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Sequ&ecirc;ncia de outras formula&ccedil;&otilde;es que se pode escolher para completar os bal&otilde;es.</p>\r\n','PRC','S',0),(91,13,'Atividade 2 - Reflita','<p>You&rsquo;ve probably noticed that the use of &ldquo;she&rdquo; referring to the actor&rsquo;s partner caused embarrassment to the actor, whose partner is a man, not a woman. So the question is: which pronoun &ndash; &ldquo;he&rdquo;, &ldquo;she&rdquo; or &ldquo;they&rdquo; &ndash; should be used with reference to words that can refer to both genders, like &ldquo;partner&rdquo;, &ldquo;student&rdquo;, &ldquo;teacher&rdquo;, &ldquo;colleague&rdquo;, &ldquo;author&rdquo;, &ldquo;doctor&rdquo;, &ldquo;person&rdquo;, among so many others? In other words, how can gender bias be avoided? For many years, people tended to use &ldquo;he&rdquo; (and &ldquo;him&rdquo;, &ldquo;his&rdquo;, &ldquo;himself&rdquo;) to refer to such words, for example:</p>\r\n\r\n<p>It&rsquo;s important to listen to your colleague&rsquo;s opinion carefully since&nbsp;<em>he</em>&nbsp;may see things from a different perspective.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>A scientist should be objective in&nbsp;<em>his</em>&nbsp;findings.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>However, this is considered to be sexist and instead, therefore some people use &ldquo;he or&nbsp;she&rdquo;:</p>\r\n\r\n<p>It&rsquo;s important to listen to your colleague&rsquo;s opinion carefully since&nbsp;<em>he or she</em>&nbsp;may see things from a different perspective.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>A scientist should be objective in&nbsp;<em>his or her</em>&nbsp;findings.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The problem is that frequent repetition of &ldquo;he or she&rdquo; slows down reading and writing. Therefore, people may choose to use third person plural pronouns: &ldquo;they&rdquo;, &ldquo;them&rdquo;, &ldquo;their&rdquo;, &ldquo;theirs&rdquo; and &ldquo;themselves&rdquo; (or &ldquo;themself&rdquo; in informal contexts). Although the use of plural pronouns to refer back to a singular subject may seem wrong, it&rsquo;s increasingly common in both written and spoken English:</p>\r\n\r\n<p>It&rsquo;s important to listen to your colleague&rsquo;s opinion carefully since&nbsp;<em>they</em>&nbsp;may see things from a different perspective.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>A scientist should be objective in&nbsp;<em>their</em>&nbsp;findings.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Can you think of other gender-neutral words? Do you believe using gender-neutral words and pronouns can help avoid sexist&nbsp;behaviour&nbsp;in general? Why (not)? In the following article, published by &ldquo;The Guardian&rdquo;, the author suggests&nbsp;that&nbsp; gender&nbsp;is a &ldquo;primary way of signifying relationships of power&rdquo;. Do you agree?&nbsp; Read the article by clicking on:</p>\r\n\r\n<p><a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/books/booksblog/2016/may/05/they-the-singular-pronoun-that-could-solve-sexism-in-english\">www.theguardian.com/books/booksblog/2016/may/05/they-the-singular-pronoun-that-could-solve-sexism-in-english</a></p>\r\n','MUL','N',0),(92,13,'Atividade 3','<p>When the TV presenter asked the actor how he got the role, he answered: &ldquo;One day my agent just <span class=\"marker\"><strong>called </strong></span>me to say that they <span class=\"marker\"><strong>were staging</strong></span> an adaptation of Jessica Richmond&rsquo;s novel&rdquo;. Can you tell the difference between the verb tenses underlined above?</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&ldquo;Were staging&rdquo; (Past Continuous) suggests something that was happening around a particular point in the past, whereas &ldquo;called&rdquo; (Past Simple) expresses the idea of a short action.&nbsp; These tenses are often used together, as in: &ldquo;I played Stanley in &ldquo;A streetcar named Desire&rdquo; two years ago, and <span class=\"marker\"><strong>was preparing</strong></span> for my first movie role when the audition <strong><span class=\"marker\">came up</span></strong>.&rdquo;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>In cases like this, the&nbsp;Past Continuous&nbsp;describes a longer, background action and the&nbsp;Past Simple&nbsp;describes the events.</p>\r\n','MUL','N',0),(93,13,'Atividade 4','<p>Bearing in mind what you learned in Activities 3 and 4, say what was happening in each of the pictures below:&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><img alt=\"\" src=\"http://labvirtual.ileel.ufu.br/lab/upload/filemanager/uploads/cellular-education-classroom-159844.jpeg\" style=\"height:387px; width:580px\" /></p>\r\n\r\n<p>Ex: The teacher was writing on the board while the student was texting</p>\r\n','MUL','N',0),(94,13,'Atividade 5','<p>Can you guess what the following underlined expressions mean?&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"margin-left:36pt\">●&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; I was preparing for my first movie role when the audition <u>came up</u>.</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"margin-left:36pt\">●&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; I think women have to <u>stand up for</u> their rights.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The expressions underlined are known as phrasal verbs. Phrasal verbs are combinations of verbs with prepositions (ex: for), adverbs (ex: up) or both (ex: up for) that function as verbs which have meanings different from the meaning of the words considered separately. In the first case, &ldquo;came up&rdquo; means &ldquo;became available&rdquo;, and in the second, &ldquo;stand up for&rdquo; means &ldquo;defend&rdquo;. Here are a few other phrasal verbs you may know:</p>\r\n\r\n<ol>\r\n	<li>Can you&nbsp;<a href=\"https://www.macmillandictionary.com/dictionary/british/turn_1\">turn</a>&nbsp;&nbsp;<u>up</u> the&nbsp;<a href=\"https://www.macmillandictionary.com/dictionary/british/volume\">air</a> conditioner a&nbsp;<a href=\"https://www.macmillandictionary.com/dictionary/british/bit_1\">bit</a>?&nbsp; (to increase the amount of sound, heat or light by pressing a button)</li>\r\n	<li>Will you&nbsp;<a href=\"https://www.macmillandictionary.com/dictionary/british/turn_1\">turn</a>&nbsp;the&nbsp;<a href=\"https://www.macmillandictionary.com/dictionary/british/music\">music</a>&nbsp;<u>down</u> a&nbsp;<a href=\"https://www.macmillandictionary.com/dictionary/british/bit_1\">bit</a>? (to reduce the amount of sound, heat or light by pressing a button)</li>\r\n	<li>Why did you <u>turn down</u> that fantastic offer? (to not accept an offer or request)</li>\r\n	<li>Frank is the most sociable person I know &ndash; he <u>gets on</u> with everyone (to have a good relationship with someone)</li>\r\n	<li>How do politicians <u>get away with</u> corruption? (to manage to do something bad without being punished or criticised for it)</li>\r\n	<li>Chris lost five kilos since she <u>took up</u> jogging. (to start doing something as a habit, job or interest)</li>\r\n	<li>I can&rsquo;t <u>take on</u> any more work right now. (to accept work or responsibility)</li>\r\n	<li>Sam started his business five years ago but it only <u>took off</u> last year. (to start to be successful or popular)</li>\r\n	<li>I <u>took to</u> Sarah immediately.(to begin to like someone or something)</li>\r\n	<li>We were terribly worried but t<a href=\"https://www.macmillandictionary.com/dictionary/british/thing\">hings</a>&nbsp;<a href=\"https://www.macmillandictionary.com/dictionary/british/work_1\">worked</a><u>&nbsp;out</u>&nbsp;<a href=\"https://www.macmillandictionary.com/dictionary/british/pretty_1\">pretty</a>&nbsp;well in the&nbsp;<a href=\"https://www.macmillandictionary.com/dictionary/british/end_1\">end</a>. (to be&nbsp;<a href=\"https://www.macmillandictionary.com/dictionary/british/successful\">successful</a>, or to&nbsp;<a href=\"https://www.macmillandictionary.com/dictionary/british/end_1\">end</a>&nbsp;in a&nbsp;<a href=\"https://www.macmillandictionary.com/dictionary/british/particular_1\">particular</a>&nbsp;way)</li>\r\n	<li>Children often <u>look up to</u> Brazilian footballers. (to&nbsp;<a href=\"https://www.macmillandictionary.com/dictionary/british/admire\">admire</a>&nbsp;and&nbsp;<a href=\"https://www.macmillandictionary.com/dictionary/british/respect_1\">respect</a>&nbsp;someone)</li>\r\n	<li>You shouldn&rsquo;t <u>look down on</u> people who don&rsquo;t earn as much as you do. (to&nbsp;<a href=\"https://www.macmillandictionary.com/dictionary/british/think_1\">think</a>&nbsp;that you are&nbsp;<a href=\"https://www.macmillandictionary.com/dictionary/british/better_1\">better</a>&nbsp;or more&nbsp;<a href=\"https://www.macmillandictionary.com/dictionary/british/important\">important</a>&nbsp;than someone else, or to&nbsp;<a href=\"https://www.macmillandictionary.com/dictionary/british/think_1\">think</a>&nbsp;that something is not&nbsp;<a href=\"https://www.macmillandictionary.com/dictionary/british/good_1\">good</a>&nbsp;enough for you)</li>\r\n	<li>At first I didn&rsquo;t <u>catch on</u> what his real intentions were. (to understand)</li>\r\n	<li>I had to <u>make up</u> an excuse about losing my key. (to invent a story, or explanation for something, in order to avoid being punished for something)</li>\r\n	<li>The children <u>made off</u> when they heard their parents arrive. (to leave quickly, especially after doing something wrong)</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n\r\n<p>The list of phrasal verbs in English is really long, and the same phrasal verb may have several meanings (as is the case of &ldquo;turn down&rdquo;, for example, as well as most of the other phrasal verbs above). The best way of learning them is by paying attention to the contexts in which they are used. In the next activity you&rsquo;ll have a chance to practice some of them.&nbsp;</p>\r\n','MUL','N',0),(95,13,'XAtividade 7','<p>In the next activity, you&rsquo;re going to hear a short question or sentence. Then you should reply using one of the phrasal verbs from the list above.&nbsp;Next&nbsp;you&rsquo;re going to hear one possible answer. Here&rsquo;s an example:</p>\r\n\r\n<p>EXAMPLE:</p>\r\n\r\n<p>(you hear) So you cannot concentrate because your&nbsp;neighbour&nbsp;is listening to loud music?&nbsp;<em>(grava&ccedil;&atilde;o em audio)</em></p>\r\n\r\n<p><em>(pausa de 8&nbsp;segundos)</em></p>\r\n\r\n<p>(you say)&nbsp;<em>Yes, I&rsquo;ll ask them to turn down the music</em>.&nbsp;<em>(grava&ccedil;&atilde;o em audio)</em></p>\r\n\r\n<p>1. So the whole story about your dog eating your homework wasn&rsquo;t true then?<em>&nbsp;(grava&ccedil;&atilde;o em audio)</em></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"margin-left:36pt\">(pausa de 8&nbsp;segundos)</p>\r\n\r\n<p><em>Yes, I just made it up. (grava&ccedil;&atilde;o em audio)</em></p>\r\n\r\n<p>2. So you two have been best buddies since you were 8 years old?&nbsp;<em>(grava&ccedil;&atilde;o em audio)</em></p>\r\n\r\n<p><em>Yes, we get on really well.</em></p>\r\n\r\n<p><em>OR</em></p>\r\n\r\n<p><em>We took to each other immediately</em>.&nbsp;<em>(grava&ccedil;&atilde;o em audio)</em></p>\r\n\r\n<p>3. If you&rsquo;re feeling bored maybe you should do something about it.&nbsp;<em>(grava&ccedil;&atilde;o em audio)</em></p>\r\n\r\n<p><em>Yes, I&rsquo;ll take up a new sport or hobby (grava&ccedil;&atilde;o em audio)</em></p>\r\n\r\n<p><em>4. So you chose to pursue the same career as your grandmother. Why? (grava&ccedil;&atilde;o em audio)</em></p>\r\n\r\n<p>Because I really look up to her<em>. (grava&ccedil;&atilde;o em audio)</em></p>\r\n\r\n<p>5. You&rsquo;ve been looking a bit stressed out lately. What&rsquo;s wrong?&nbsp;<em>(grava&ccedil;&atilde;o em audio)</em></p>\r\n\r\n<p><em>Maybe I&rsquo;ve taken on too much work. (grava&ccedil;&atilde;o em audio)</em></p>\r\n\r\n<p>6. So the police have no idea who stole one million euros from the bank?&nbsp;<em>(grava&ccedil;&atilde;o em audio)</em></p>\r\n\r\n<p><em>Yes, the thieves made off before the police arrived.</em>&nbsp;<em>(grava&ccedil;&atilde;o em audio)</em></p>\r\n\r\n<p><em>7. Why did you get up and leave in the middle of our philosophy lesson? (grava&ccedil;&atilde;o em audio)</em></p>\r\n\r\n<p><em>Because I couldn&rsquo;t catch on any of the teacher&rsquo;s explanations.</em></p>\r\n\r\n<p><em>8.&nbsp;So&nbsp;you&rsquo;re a volunteer for the &ldquo;The welfare of stray dogs&rdquo;. It&rsquo;s an NGO, right? (grava&ccedil;&atilde;o em audio)</em></p>\r\n\r\n<p><em>Yes, I think it&rsquo;s important to stand up for the rights of stray animals.</em></p>\r\n','RPT','S',0),(96,14,'Atividade 1','<p>Listening and repetition</p>\r\n','RPT','S',0),(97,14,'Atividade 2: Building knowledge together','<p><strong><u>A relevant example I read</u></strong>&nbsp;on this matter is the account Lee&nbsp;presentes&nbsp;in his book&nbsp;....</p>\r\n\r\n<p>1.&nbsp; Stating&nbsp; Opinions&nbsp;&nbsp; I think__ because __. I (firmly, strongly) believe __. In my opinion, __. From my perspective, __. I am convinced __. My opinion on this (topic, issue) is __.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>3.&nbsp; Supporting&nbsp; /&nbsp; Elaborating&nbsp;&nbsp; For (example, instance), __. A relevant example I (heard, read) was __. One (possible, convincing) reason is __. A (key, major) reason is __.&nbsp; A relevant experience I had was __.&nbsp; I experienced this when __.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>3.&nbsp; Providing&nbsp; Evidence&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; After hearing __, I am convinced __.&nbsp; The data on __ suggests __. After reading __, I conclude that __.&nbsp; After reviewing __, I assume that __. Drawing from experience, I know that __. Based on experience, it seems evident that __.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>4.&nbsp; Comparing&nbsp; /&nbsp; Contrasting&nbsp;&nbsp; My (idea, response) is similar to (Name&rsquo;s). My (opinion, perspective) is similar to (Name&rsquo;s). My response is similar to that of my classmates. My response is different from (Name&rsquo;s). My (approach, perspective) is different from (Name&rsquo;s). My (analysis, conclusion, solution) is different from (Name&rsquo;s).</p>\r\n\r\n<p>5.&nbsp; Agreeing&nbsp; /&nbsp; Disagreeing&nbsp;&nbsp; I (completely) agree with (Name) that __. I share your perspective.&nbsp; My idea builds upon (Name&rsquo;s).&nbsp; I don&rsquo;t (quite, entirely) agree. I disagree (somewhat, completely).&nbsp; I have a different perspective on this (topic, issue).</p>\r\n\r\n<p>1.&nbsp; Eliciting&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; What should we (say, put, write)? What do you think makes sense? What&rsquo;s your (idea, opinion, experience)? Do you have anything to add? How would you (approach, complete) this task?&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>2.&nbsp; Contributing&nbsp; /&nbsp; Suggesting&nbsp;&nbsp; We could (say, put, write) __. What if we (say, put, write) __. I think __ makes the most sense. I think __ would work well. I think we should (add, include, consider) __.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>3.&nbsp; Validating&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; That would work. That makes sense. That&rsquo;s a great (idea, suggestion). I see what you&rsquo;re saying.&nbsp; That&rsquo;s worth considering.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>4.&nbsp; Negotiating&nbsp;&nbsp; Let&rsquo;s (say, put, use, write) __ because __.&nbsp; Let&rsquo;s go with (Name&rsquo;s) suggestion __. I still think __ is the strongest (choice, response). Let&rsquo;s combine ideas and put __. What if we (began, concluded) by __.&nbsp;&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>5.&nbsp; Clarifying&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; I don&rsquo;t quite understand your (idea, reason). I have a question about __. What exactly do you mean by __? If I understand you correctly, you think that _? Are you suggesting __?</p>\r\n\r\n<p>6.&nbsp; Restating&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; So, you think that __. So, your (idea, opinion, response) is__. So, you&rsquo;re suggesting that __.&nbsp; Yes, that&rsquo;s (right, correct).&nbsp; No, not exactly. What I (said, meant) was __.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp; 7.&nbsp; Reporting&nbsp;&nbsp; We (decided, concluded, determined) that __&nbsp;because&nbsp;__. One (fact, reason,&nbsp;piece&nbsp;of evidence) we considered is __. Our (point of view, response, conclusion) is that __.&nbsp;&nbsp; After reviewing __, we concluded that __. We came up with a __(similar, different) response.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>8.&nbsp; Listening&nbsp; Attentively&nbsp;&nbsp; The (idea/example) I __ (added/recorded) was __. I (appreciated/related) to (Name&rsquo;s) __(example/experience). The most convincing reason I heard was __. The strongest (argument/evidence) offered was __. The contribution I (appreciated, added, selected) was __.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<table border=\"1\" cellpadding=\"0\" cellspacing=\"0\" style=\"width:608px\">\r\n	<tbody>\r\n		<tr>\r\n			<td style=\"height:101px; width:152px\">\r\n			<p><strong>Express&otilde;es para expor opini&otilde;es</strong></p>\r\n\r\n			<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n			</td>\r\n			<td style=\"height:101px; width:152px\">\r\n			<p><strong>Express&otilde;es para concordar</strong></p>\r\n			</td>\r\n			<td style=\"height:101px; width:152px\">\r\n			<p><strong>Express&otilde;es para discordar</strong></p>\r\n			</td>\r\n			<td style=\"height:101px; width:152px\">\r\n			<p><strong>Express&otilde;es para exemplificar ou apresentar argumentos</strong></p>\r\n			</td>\r\n		</tr>\r\n		<tr>\r\n			<td style=\"height:65px; width:152px\">\r\n			<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n			</td>\r\n			<td style=\"height:65px; width:152px\">\r\n			<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n			</td>\r\n			<td style=\"height:65px; width:152px\">\r\n			<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n			</td>\r\n			<td style=\"height:65px; width:152px\">\r\n			<p><em>A relevant example I read</em></p>\r\n			</td>\r\n		</tr>\r\n	</tbody>\r\n</table>\r\n','PRC','S',0),(98,14,'Atividade 3','<p>Substitua as express&otilde;es grifadas por outras formula&ccedil;&otilde;es, usando as express&otilde;es entre par&ecirc;nteses. Grave suas respostas e envie para obter um feedback.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Nadine: _ Hmmm, I think we have reached an impass in our discussion.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Rosa: _ I <strong>think</strong> we could use a break.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>(believe ∕&nbsp; In my opinion, ∕ From my perspective)</p>\r\n\r\n<p>(Respostas: I believe we could use a break.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>In my opinion, we could use a break.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>From my perspective, we could use a break.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Daniel: _<strong>That&acute;s<br />\r\na good idea</strong>.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>(agree)</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Resposta: I agree.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Ben&iacute;cio: _ <strong>Maybe<br />\r\nwe could have</strong> an inspiring break. What do you say we go see that art<br />\r\nexhibit I told you about?</p>\r\n\r\n<p>(What if ∕ I think we should)</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Respostas: What if we have an inspiring break?</p>\r\n\r\n<p>I think we should have an inspiring break.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>[Some time later...]</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Nadine: _ So, <strong>what are your thoughts</strong> on the exbhibitions we&acute;ve just seen?</p>\r\n\r\n<p>(What do you think)</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Resposta: What do you think of the exhibitions we&acute;ve just seen?</p>\r\n','MUL','S',0),(99,14,'Atividade 4','<p style=\"margin-left:58pt\">1.&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; I strongly believe....</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"margin-left:58pt\">2.&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; That makes sense.</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"margin-left:58pt\">3.&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; My response is similar to my colleague&acute;s.</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"margin-left:58pt\">4.&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; My opinion on this topic is....</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"margin-left:58pt\">5.&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; I share your perspective on this issue.</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"margin-left:58pt\">6.&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; How would you approach this task?</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"margin-left:58pt\">7.&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; So when you say that it ...., do you mean......?</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"margin-left:58pt\">8.&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; The idea that you added is really interesting in the sense that...</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"margin-left:58pt\">9.&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; The strongest argument I can offer is.....</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"margin-left:58pt\">10.&nbsp; Let&acute;s say this is a valid example, if I understand the question correctly, you think that....?</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"margin-left:58pt\">11. So, to wrap it up&hellip;.</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"margin-left:58pt\">12.&nbsp; After hearing my colleagues, I conclude that....?</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"margin-left:58pt\">13.&nbsp; One fact we certainly should consider is.....</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"margin-left:58pt\">14.&nbsp; The most convincing reason I heard was ....</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"margin-left:58pt\">15.&nbsp;&nbsp; Drawing from my experience, I know that....</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"margin-left:58pt\">16.&nbsp; Your approach is different in the sense that....</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"margin-left:58pt\">17.&nbsp; I believe we can conclude that...</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"margin-left:58pt\">18.&nbsp; After reviewing everybody&acute;s contribution, we came up with ...&nbsp;</p>\r\n','PRN','S',0),(100,14,'Atividade 5: What´s art?','<p><strong>Talking about art</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>Dialogue 1: Talking about feelings and sensations</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>Dialogue 2: Discussing a performance</strong></p>\r\n','MUL','S',0),(101,14,'Atividade 6','<p>Onomatopoeic words</p>\r\n','RPT','S',0),(102,14,'Atividade 7','<p>Poems of Sappho</p>\r\n\r\n<p>David</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Public domain images</p>\r\n','MUL','S',0),(103,15,'Atividade 1','<p><strong>1 - Expanding a dictionary definition</strong></p>\r\n','MUL','N',0),(104,15,'Atividade 2','<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><strong>2 - In a salad bowl</strong></p>\r\n','MUL','N',0),(105,15,'Atividade 3','<p><strong>3 - Translingual practices</strong></p>\r\n','MUL','S',0),(106,15,'Atividade 4','<p><strong>4 - Leaving my country</strong></p>\r\n','MUL','S',0),(107,16,'1 - Atividade teste mídias','<p>Esta atividade faz refer&ecirc;ncia ao teste de m&iacute;dias do laborat&oacute;rio</p>\r\n','RPT','S',0),(108,16,'Balões em Branco','','PRC','S',1),(109,16,'tema 3','','VID','S',2),(110,16,'Teste 4','<p>teste</p>\r\n','EMO','S',13),(112,18,'Teste Várias Mídias multipla escolha','','MUL','S',0),(113,16,'teste task pronúncia','','PRN','S',0),(116,16,'detecção de emoção','<p>detec&ccedil;&atilde;o de emo&ccedil;&atilde;o</p>\r\n','EMO','S',10),(117,16,'emoção por imagem','<p>voz</p>\r\n','EMI','S',11),(118,18,'Atividade replicação de multipla escolha','','PRC','S',3),(119,18,'Teste com áudios na multipla escolha','','PRC','S',4),(120,9,'Atividade 4: Wrapping it up!','<p>As situa&ccedil;&otilde;es apresentadas nos audios 1, 2 e 3 nos fazem pensar em (im)possibilidades enunciativas, ou seja, no fato de que nem tudo pode ser dito &ndash; seja em l&iacute;ngua materna ou estrangeira. E tal impossibilidade deve-se n&atilde;o apenas por uma suposta falta de profici&ecirc;ncia do falante, mas a fatores que remetem &agrave; rela&ccedil;&atilde;o da l&iacute;ngua com a hist&oacute;ria, dos sentidos com os quais os sujeitos se identificam, das condi&ccedil;&otilde;es de produ&ccedil;&atilde;o da enuncia&ccedil;&atilde;o (que s&atilde;o &uacute;nicas e irrepet&iacute;veis), das imagens que o interlocutor tem de si e do(s) outro(s). Ademais, h&aacute; de se considerar que essas (im)possibilidades dizem respeito &agrave; natureza sempre tensa e conflitiva da tomada significante da palavra, j&aacute; que, ao significar o mundo, nos significamos &lsquo;no&rsquo; mundo. Ou seja, ao dizer (d)o outro, digo de mim, me posiciono em rela&ccedil;&atilde;o ao outro e o posiciono em rela&ccedil;&atilde;o a mim.</p>\r\n','MUL','N',0),(121,11,'Atividade 6: Deduções por modais','<p>Usamos os verbos modais para dizer qu&atilde;o certos estamos sobre algo</p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li><strong>must </strong></li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<p>We use must when we feel sure that something is true because there&rsquo;s very strong evidence.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>He must live near here because he comes to work on foot. We don&rsquo;t know where he lives but we&rsquo;re sure it&rsquo;s not far away.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Come inside and get warm &ndash; you must be freezing out there.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>You&rsquo;re a zookeeper? That must be very interesting.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Notice that must is followed by an infinitive without &lsquo;to&rsquo;.</p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li><strong>might, may, could</strong></li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<p>We use might, may or could to say that we think something is possible but we&rsquo;re not sure.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Did you hear that? I think there might be a burglar downstairs. She&rsquo;s not sure there&rsquo;s a burglar but she thinks it&rsquo;s possible.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>We&rsquo;ll try to get there early but we may arrive late if there&rsquo;s a lot of traffic.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Don&rsquo;t put it up there. It could fall off and hit someone.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Might, may and could are also followed by an infinitive without &lsquo;to&rsquo;.</p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li><strong>can&rsquo;t</strong></li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<p>We use can&rsquo;t when we feel sure something is not true.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>It can&rsquo;t be a burglar. All the doors and windows are locked. He doesn&rsquo;t know it&rsquo;s not a burglar but he feels sure it&rsquo;s not.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>It can&rsquo;t be far away now. We&rsquo;ve been driving for hours. Where&rsquo;s the map?</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Really? He has to work on Christmas Day? He can&rsquo;t feel very happy about that.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Like the other verbs, can&rsquo;t is followed by an infinitive without &lsquo;to&rsquo;.</p>\r\n','MUL','N',0),(122,11,'Atividade 7: Reflita a respeito','<p>Usando suas pr&oacute;prias palavras, voc&ecirc; poderia nos dizer o que &eacute; &#39;Ebonics&#39;?</p>\r\n','RPT','N',0),(123,8,'LA','','PRC','S',0),(125,18,'Atividade Teste Bella','','PRC','S',6),(126,8,'Título atividade','<p><em>Quais outras formula&ccedil;&otilde;es poder&iacute;amos dizer para completar os bal&otilde;es e manter o tom amig&aacute;vel das conversas originais das personagens? Para cada lacuna, escolha uma das 03 op&ccedil;&otilde;es propostas e fale-a em seu microfone para obter um feedback. &Agrave;s vezes, mais de uma op&ccedil;&atilde;o &eacute; correta.</em></p>\r\n','RPT','S',0),(129,21,'Practicing consonant phonemes','<div class=\"tw-ta-container tw-nfl\" id=\"tw-target-text-container\">\r\n<pre style=\"text-align:left\">\r\nVamos praticar fonemas de consoantes. Por favor, assista os v&iacute;deos, pause-os e repita-os. Preste aten&ccedil;&atilde;o aos seus pontos de articula&ccedil;&atilde;o e nas diferen&ccedil;as de som e movimentos da boca.</pre>\r\n\r\n<pre>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;</pre>\r\n</div>\r\n\r\n<pre style=\"text-align:left\">\r\n\r\n&nbsp;</pre>\r\n','PRN','S',1),(130,21,'Prática de fonemas de vogais','<p>Agora, vamos praticar os fonemas de vogais. Por favor, assista os v&iacute;deos e repita os sons.</p>\r\n','','S',11),(134,18,'lacunas exemplo','','PRC','S',2),(135,22,'Prática de pronúncia de fonemas de vogais','<p>Nesta atividade, convidamos voc&ecirc; a assistir os v&iacute;deos com vogais e palavras de exemplo das vogais e repeti-las. Vamos l&aacute;?</p>\r\n','PRN','N',8),(137,15,'Atividade 5 - Family as a rhizome','<p><strong>5-&nbsp;Family as a rhizome</strong></p>\r\n','MUL','S',0),(138,15,'Atividade 3 - Translingual practices','<p><span style=\"font-size:14px\"><strong>3-&nbsp;Translingual practices</strong></span></p>\r\n','PRN','S',0),(139,8,'Atividade de teste','<p>teste</p>\r\n','MUL','S',0),(140,8,'Atividade 2: Diferentes formulações','<p><em>Quais outras formula&ccedil;&otilde;es poder&iacute;amos dizer para completar os bal&otilde;es e manter o tom amig&aacute;vel das conversas originais das personagens? Para cada lacuna, escolha uma das 03 op&ccedil;&otilde;es propostas e fale-a em seu microfone para obter um feedback. &Agrave;s vezes, mais de uma op&ccedil;&atilde;o &eacute; correta.</em></p>\r\n','MUL','S',0),(141,18,'testes','','PRN','S',0),(142,15,'3 - Translingual practices','<p><strong>Atividade 3 - Translingual practices</strong></p>\r\n','MUL','N',0),(143,15,'Atividade 4 - Leaving my country','<p><strong>Atividade 4 - Leaving my country</strong></p>\r\n','MUL','S',0),(144,15,'Atividade 4 - Family as a rhizome','<p><strong>Atividade 4&nbsp;- Family as a rhizome</strong></p>\r\n','MUL','N',0),(145,15,'Atividade 6 - Where are you from?','<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><strong>Atividade 6 - Where are you from?</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<div>&nbsp;</div>\r\n','MUL','S',0),(147,22,'Videoaula de fonética e fonologia do inglês ','<p>Videoaula.</p>\r\n','VID','N',1),(148,18,'colunas','','REL','S',0),(150,18,'teste','<p>Teste</p>\r\n\r\n<div class=\"row\">\r\n<div class=\"col-xs-12\">\r\n<div class=\"alert alert-block alert-warning\">&times;</div>\r\n\r\n<div class=\"alert alert-block alert-warning\">&times;</div>\r\n</div>\r\n</div>\r\n','PRN','S',6),(151,14,'Aula 7 – Tema: Arte e linguagem','<p><strong>Art for thought</strong></p>\r\n','RPT','S',0),(152,14,'Atividade 1','<p><span style=\"font-size:14px\">Atividade 1&nbsp;</span></p>\r\n\r\n<div>&nbsp;</div>\r\n','RPT','N',0),(153,12,'Atividade 1','<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"background-color:transparent; color:rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family:arial; font-size:12pt\">&ldquo;A Day in the Life of Women (2018 version)&rdquo; is a short animation that tells us about the daily routines of four female characters: Ana, Maria, Lucia and Stela, who portray situations that many real women experience in their lives. They are hardworking, dignified people who have to </span><span style=\"background-color:transparent; color:rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family:arial; font-size:12pt\">put up with</span><span style=\"background-color:transparent; color:rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family:arial; font-size:12pt\"> </span><span style=\"background-color:transparent; color:rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family:arial; font-size:12pt\">sexism</span><span style=\"background-color:transparent; color:rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family:arial; font-size:12pt\"> and oppression in forms that vary from minor offenses to sexual harassment and violence.&nbsp; </span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<div dir=\"ltr\" style=\"margin-left:222.75pt;\">\r\n<table style=\"border-collapse:collapse; border:none\">\r\n	<tbody>\r\n		<tr>\r\n			<td style=\"vertical-align:top\">\r\n			<p><strong>Quick notes:</strong></p>\r\n			&nbsp;\r\n\r\n			<p><strong>Put up with</strong><span style=\"background-color:transparent; color:rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family:arial; font-size:10pt\"> (/ˈpʊtˈʌp</span><a href=\"https://easypronunciation.com/\" style=\"text-decoration-line: none;\"><span style=\"background-color:transparent; color:rgb(17, 85, 204); font-family:arial; font-size:10pt\">ˈwɪ&theta;/)</span></a><span style=\"background-color:transparent; color:rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family:arial; font-size:10pt\"> = tolerate, endure</span></p>\r\n			&nbsp;\r\n\r\n			<p><strong>Sexism </strong><span style=\"background-color:transparent; color:rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family:arial; font-size:10pt\">(/ˈsekˌsizəm/)= prejudice, discrimination or stereotyping based on sexual identifications</span></p>\r\n			&nbsp;\r\n\r\n			<p><strong>Harassment</strong><span style=\"background-color:transparent; color:rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family:arial; font-size:10pt\"> (/həˈrasmənt,ˈherəsmənt/) = intimidation or aggressive behavior that demeans, humiliates or embarrasses a person</span></p>\r\n			</td>\r\n		</tr>\r\n	</tbody>\r\n</table>\r\n</div>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"background-color:transparent; color:rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family:arial; font-size:12pt\">But&nbsp; what can be considered harassment? How does it take place? Let us read this definition by the United Nations Entity for Gender Equality and the Empowerment of Women:</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><strong>Text 1</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<div dir=\"ltr\" style=\"margin-left:0pt;\">\r\n<table style=\"border-collapse:collapse; border:none; width:474.8255905511812pt\">\r\n	<tbody>\r\n		<tr>\r\n			<td style=\"vertical-align:top\">\r\n			<h1><strong>Prohibition of discrimination, harassment, including sexual harassment, and abuse of authority</strong></h1>\r\n\r\n			<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"background-color:transparent; color:rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family:arial; font-size:11pt\">Discrimination, sexual harassment and harassment are defined in SG&#39;s bulletin</span><a href=\"http://daccess-ods.un.org/access.nsf/Get?Open&amp;DS=ST/SGB/2008/5&amp;Lang=E\" style=\"text-decoration-line: none;\"><span style=\"background-color:transparent; color:rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family:arial; font-size:11pt\"> </span><span style=\"background-color:transparent; color:rgb(17, 85, 204); font-family:arial; font-size:11pt\">ST/SGB/2008/5</span></a></p>\r\n\r\n			<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"background-color:transparent; color:rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family:arial; font-size:11pt\">Discrimination is any unfair treatment or arbitrary distinction based on a person&rsquo;s race, sex, religion, nationality, ethnic origin, sexual orientation, disability, age, language, social origin or other status. Discrimination may be an isolated event affecting one person or a group of persons similarly situated, or may manifest itself through harassment or abuse of authority.</span></p>\r\n\r\n			<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"background-color:transparent; color:rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family:arial; font-size:11pt\">Harassment is any improper and unwelcome conduct that might reasonably be expected or be perceived to cause offence or humiliation to another person. Harassment may take the form of words, gestures or actions which tend to annoy, alarm, abuse, demean, intimidate, belittle, humiliate or embarrass another or which create an intimidating, hostile or offensive work environment. Harassment normally implies a series of incidents. Disagreement on work performance or on other work-related issues is normally not considered harassment and is not dealt with under the provisions of this policy but in the context of performance management.</span></p>\r\n\r\n			<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"background-color:transparent; color:rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family:arial; font-size:11pt\">Sexual harassment is any unwelcome sexual advance, request for sexual favour, verbal or physical conduct or gesture of a sexual nature, or any other behaviour of a sexual nature that might reasonably be expected or be perceived to cause offence or humiliation to another, when such conduct interferes with work, is made a condition of employment or creates an intimidating, hostile or offensive work environment. While typically involving a pattern of behaviour, it can take the form of a single incident. Sexual harassment may occur between persons of the opposite or same sex. Both males and females can be either the victims or the offenders.</span></p>\r\n			&nbsp;\r\n\r\n			<p><span style=\"background-color:transparent; color:rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family:arial; font-size:10pt\">Source: </span><a href=\"https://www.un.org/womenwatch/osagi/fpsexualharassment.htm\" style=\"text-decoration-line: none;\"><span style=\"background-color:transparent; color:rgb(17, 85, 204); font-family:arial; font-size:10pt\">https://www.un.org/womenwatch/osagi/fpsexualharassment.htm</span></a><span style=\"background-color:transparent; color:rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family:arial; font-size:10pt\">. Access: 07/07/2019.</span></p>\r\n			</td>\r\n		</tr>\r\n	</tbody>\r\n</table>\r\n</div>\r\n','REL','N',0),(154,12,'Atividade 3','','MUL','S',2),(155,14,'Atividade 2','<p><strong>Atividade 2</strong></p>\r\n','RPT','N',0),(158,12,'Atividade 3','','MUL','N',2),(159,12,'Atividade 2','<p>In&nbsp; &ldquo;A Day in the Life of Women&rdquo;, the narrator describes the activities our characters do on a daily basis. When we express states and habits, we use the verb tense called <em>simple present</em>. According to El-Dash (2013), verb tenses in English can be organized in the following scheme:</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>Table 1: Semantic scheme of English verb tenses</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<table border=\"1\" cellpadding=\"0\" cellspacing=\"0\" style=\"width:633px\">\r\n	<tbody>\r\n		<tr>\r\n			<td style=\"width:103px\">\r\n			<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n			</td>\r\n			<td style=\"width:273px\">\r\n			<p><strong>Limitless</strong></p>\r\n			</td>\r\n			<td style=\"width:257px\">\r\n			<p><strong>Limited</strong></p>\r\n			</td>\r\n		</tr>\r\n		<tr>\r\n			<td style=\"width:103px\">\r\n			<p><strong>Existence</strong></p>\r\n			</td>\r\n			<td style=\"width:273px\">\r\n			<p>Now: simple present</p>\r\n\r\n			<p>Distanced from now: simple past</p>\r\n			</td>\r\n			<td style=\"width:257px\">\r\n			<p>Now = present perfect</p>\r\n\r\n			<p>Distanced from now = past perfect</p>\r\n			</td>\r\n		</tr>\r\n		<tr>\r\n			<td style=\"width:103px\">\r\n			<p><strong>Action</strong></p>\r\n			</td>\r\n			<td style=\"width:273px\">\r\n			<p>Now = present progressive</p>\r\n\r\n			<p>Distanced from now = past progressive</p>\r\n			</td>\r\n			<td style=\"width:257px\">\r\n			<p>Now = present perfect progressive</p>\r\n\r\n			<p>Distanced from now = past perfect progressive</p>\r\n			</td>\r\n		</tr>\r\n	</tbody>\r\n</table>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>Source: Translated from El Dash (2013, p. 1)</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>From this scheme, we can understand the simple present expresses &ldquo;limitless existence&rdquo;, that is, it is a verb tense that <u>expresses existing states or habits</u>, and not actions. According to El Dash (idem), such distinction and categorization is difficult for Portuguese speakers to understand because our semantics is different: in Portuguese, we differentiate between state and action, focusing on the meaning of the verbs. In English, however, when we use verbs such as <em>work</em>, <em>get up</em>, <em>take</em> (the bus), <em>clean</em> (the house), <em>play</em>, etc., in the simple present, it is not the action itself that is the focal point of the statement, but the effect of repetition marked by the tense, which creates the sense of a state, that is, the effect of engagement of the subject in an action, so that it becomes a habit. Thus, when one says: &ldquo;Ana gets to work on time.&rdquo;, the emphasis is on her habit to get to work on time and not on getting to work. The simple present also expresses situations that are believed to be <u>true facts or certain from the point of view of the subject</u>:</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li><em>Ana chooses a piece of clothing.</em> (I see her doing that, I am certain of what she did.)</li>\r\n	<li><em>Maria raises her daughter alone</em>. (I see her doing that, I am certain of it.)</li>\r\n	<li><em>Dogs have four legs. </em></li>\r\n	<li><em>I am from Brazil.</em></li>\r\n	<li><em>The presidential palace is in Bras&iacute;lia. </em></li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>It is even used to refer to situations in the future, when one is sure about the future. As El Dash (2013, p. 12) exemplifies:</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li><em>The bus leaves at noon tomorrow.</em> (The bus always leaves at noon, so it will do it tomorrow again.)</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li><em>I graduate in June.</em> (I do not see any possibility of failure in my studies now that would prevent me from graduating in June)</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The simple present has some specific grammar rules:</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<ol>\r\n	<li>Affirmative sentences</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"margin-left:36.0pt\">In affirmative sentences, the simple present obbeys the general syntactic sequence, subject, verb, complement:</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"margin-left:36.0pt\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"margin-left:36.0pt\"><strong>Table 2: Examples in the simple present tense</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<table border=\"1\" cellpadding=\"0\" cellspacing=\"0\" style=\"width:585px\">\r\n	<tbody>\r\n		<tr>\r\n			<td style=\"width:195px\">\r\n			<p><strong>Subject</strong></p>\r\n			</td>\r\n			<td style=\"width:108px\">\r\n			<p><strong>Verb</strong></p>\r\n			</td>\r\n			<td style=\"width:282px\">\r\n			<p><strong>Complement</strong></p>\r\n			</td>\r\n		</tr>\r\n		<tr>\r\n			<td style=\"width:195px\">\r\n			<p>Stela</p>\r\n			</td>\r\n			<td style=\"width:108px\">\r\n			<p>plays</p>\r\n			</td>\r\n			<td style=\"width:282px\">\r\n			<p>the violin.</p>\r\n			</td>\r\n		</tr>\r\n		<tr>\r\n			<td style=\"width:195px\">\r\n			<p>Maria</p>\r\n			</td>\r\n			<td style=\"width:108px\">\r\n			<p>takes</p>\r\n			</td>\r\n			<td style=\"width:282px\">\r\n			<p>the bus to work.</p>\r\n			</td>\r\n		</tr>\r\n		<tr>\r\n			<td style=\"width:195px\">\r\n			<p>Matilda</p>\r\n			</td>\r\n			<td style=\"width:108px\">\r\n			<p>stays</p>\r\n			</td>\r\n			<td style=\"width:282px\">\r\n			<p>at day care during the day.</p>\r\n			</td>\r\n		</tr>\r\n		<tr>\r\n			<td style=\"width:195px\">\r\n			<p>Few women</p>\r\n			</td>\r\n			<td style=\"width:108px\">\r\n			<p>work</p>\r\n			</td>\r\n			<td style=\"width:282px\">\r\n			<p>in management positions.</p>\r\n			</td>\r\n		</tr>\r\n		<tr>\r\n			<td style=\"width:195px\">\r\n			<p>I</p>\r\n			</td>\r\n			<td style=\"width:108px\">\r\n			<p>read</p>\r\n			</td>\r\n			<td style=\"width:282px\">\r\n			<p>the examples in the explanations.</p>\r\n			</td>\r\n		</tr>\r\n		<tr>\r\n			<td style=\"width:195px\">\r\n			<p>Some men</p>\r\n			</td>\r\n			<td style=\"width:108px\">\r\n			<p>tend</p>\r\n			</td>\r\n			<td style=\"width:282px\">\r\n			<p>to oppress women.</p>\r\n			</td>\r\n		</tr>\r\n		<tr>\r\n			<td style=\"width:195px\">\r\n			<p>We</p>\r\n			</td>\r\n			<td style=\"width:108px\">\r\n			<p>have</p>\r\n			</td>\r\n			<td style=\"width:282px\">\r\n			<p>to protect each other</p>\r\n			</td>\r\n		</tr>\r\n		<tr>\r\n			<td style=\"width:195px\">\r\n			<p>You</p>\r\n			</td>\r\n			<td style=\"width:108px\">\r\n			<p>work</p>\r\n			</td>\r\n			<td style=\"width:282px\">\r\n			<p>full time.</p>\r\n			</td>\r\n		</tr>\r\n	</tbody>\r\n</table>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"margin-left:36.0pt\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>It is important to observe that the linguistic form of the verbs vary according to the subject. Subjects such as <em>Stela</em>, <em>Maria</em> and <em>Matilda</em> are what we call the <u>third person singular</u>. When we have this kind of subject, we add&nbsp; &ldquo;S&rdquo; to the verb:</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Stela plays</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Maria takes</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Matilda stays</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>In some cases, instead of S we add &ldquo;ES&rdquo; or &ldquo;IES&rdquo;. Take a look at the rules:</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>Verbs ending in <em>-ss, -sh, -ch, -x</em> and <em>-o</em> takes &ldquo;ES&rdquo;: She teach<strong>es</strong> Statistics.</li>\r\n	<li>Verbs ending in a consonant +y, drop the y and take -IES: Stela stud<strong>ies</strong> music.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The subjects<em> Few women</em>,<em> I</em>, and <em>Some men</em>, <em>We</em> and <em>You</em>, on the other hand, do not need the &ldquo;S&rdquo;.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"margin-left:36.0pt\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<ol>\r\n	<li>Negative sentences</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"margin-left:36.0pt\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>To make negative sentences in the simple present, we usually use <strong>do not</strong> (or don&rsquo;t) and <strong>does not</strong> (or doesn&rsquo;t) for the third person singular. In this case, we do not need to add the &ldquo;S&rdquo; to the main verb anymore. Let us see how the examples in Table 2 can be transformed in negative sentences:</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"margin-left:36.0pt\"><strong>Table 3: Examples of sentences in the simple present in the negative form</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<table border=\"1\" cellpadding=\"0\" cellspacing=\"0\" style=\"width:586px\">\r\n	<tbody>\r\n		<tr>\r\n			<td style=\"width:103px\">\r\n			<p><strong>Subject</strong></p>\r\n			</td>\r\n			<td style=\"width:148px\">\r\n			<p><strong>don&rsquo;t or doesn&rsquo;t</strong></p>\r\n			</td>\r\n			<td style=\"width:149px\">\r\n			<p><strong>Verb</strong></p>\r\n			</td>\r\n			<td style=\"width:187px\">\r\n			<p><strong>Complement</strong></p>\r\n			</td>\r\n		</tr>\r\n		<tr>\r\n			<td style=\"width:103px\">\r\n			<p>Stela</p>\r\n			</td>\r\n			<td style=\"width:148px\">\r\n			<p>doesn&rsquo;t</p>\r\n			</td>\r\n			<td style=\"width:149px\">\r\n			<p>play</p>\r\n			</td>\r\n			<td style=\"width:187px\">\r\n			<p>the violin.</p>\r\n			</td>\r\n		</tr>\r\n		<tr>\r\n			<td style=\"width:103px\">\r\n			<p>Maria</p>\r\n			</td>\r\n			<td style=\"width:148px\">\r\n			<p>doesn&rsquo;t</p>\r\n			</td>\r\n			<td style=\"width:149px\">\r\n			<p>take</p>\r\n			</td>\r\n			<td style=\"width:187px\">\r\n			<p>the bus to work.</p>\r\n			</td>\r\n		</tr>\r\n		<tr>\r\n			<td style=\"width:103px\">\r\n			<p>Matilda</p>\r\n			</td>\r\n			<td style=\"width:148px\">\r\n			<p>doesn&rsquo;t</p>\r\n			</td>\r\n			<td style=\"width:149px\">\r\n			<p>stay</p>\r\n			</td>\r\n			<td style=\"width:187px\">\r\n			<p>at day care during the day.</p>\r\n			</td>\r\n		</tr>\r\n		<tr>\r\n			<td style=\"width:103px\">\r\n			<p>Few women</p>\r\n			</td>\r\n			<td style=\"width:148px\">\r\n			<p>don&rsquo;t</p>\r\n			</td>\r\n			<td style=\"width:149px\">\r\n			<p>work</p>\r\n			</td>\r\n			<td style=\"width:187px\">\r\n			<p>in management positions.</p>\r\n			</td>\r\n		</tr>\r\n		<tr>\r\n			<td style=\"width:103px\">\r\n			<p>I</p>\r\n			</td>\r\n			<td style=\"width:148px\">\r\n			<p>don&rsquo;t</p>\r\n			</td>\r\n			<td style=\"width:149px\">\r\n			<p>read</p>\r\n			</td>\r\n			<td style=\"width:187px\">\r\n			<p>the examples in the explanations.</p>\r\n			</td>\r\n		</tr>\r\n		<tr>\r\n			<td style=\"width:103px\">\r\n			<p>Some men</p>\r\n			</td>\r\n			<td style=\"width:148px\">\r\n			<p>don&rsquo;t</p>\r\n			</td>\r\n			<td style=\"width:149px\">\r\n			<p>tend</p>\r\n			</td>\r\n			<td style=\"width:187px\">\r\n			<p>to oppress women.</p>\r\n			</td>\r\n		</tr>\r\n		<tr>\r\n			<td style=\"width:103px\">\r\n			<p>We</p>\r\n			</td>\r\n			<td style=\"width:148px\">\r\n			<p>don&rsquo;t</p>\r\n			</td>\r\n			<td style=\"width:149px\">\r\n			<p>have</p>\r\n			</td>\r\n			<td style=\"width:187px\">\r\n			<p>to protect each other</p>\r\n			</td>\r\n		</tr>\r\n		<tr>\r\n			<td style=\"width:103px\">\r\n			<p>You</p>\r\n			</td>\r\n			<td style=\"width:148px\">\r\n			<p>don&rsquo;t</p>\r\n			</td>\r\n			<td style=\"width:149px\">\r\n			<p>work</p>\r\n			</td>\r\n			<td style=\"width:187px\">\r\n			<p>full time.</p>\r\n			</td>\r\n		</tr>\r\n	</tbody>\r\n</table>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"margin-left:36.0pt\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"margin-left:36.0pt\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<ol>\r\n	<li>Interrogative sentences</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>We use &lsquo;Do&rsquo; or &lsquo;Does&rsquo; before the subject to make the &#39;yes / no&#39; questions.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"margin-left:36.0pt\"><strong>Table 4: Examples of sentences in the simple present in the interrogative form</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<table border=\"1\" cellpadding=\"0\" cellspacing=\"0\" style=\"width:460px\">\r\n	<tbody>\r\n		<tr>\r\n			<td style=\"width:87px\">\r\n			<p><strong>Do or Does</strong></p>\r\n			</td>\r\n			<td style=\"width:87px\">\r\n			<p><strong>Subject</strong></p>\r\n			</td>\r\n			<td style=\"width:127px\">\r\n			<p><strong>Verb</strong></p>\r\n			</td>\r\n			<td style=\"width:159px\">\r\n			<p><strong>Complement</strong></p>\r\n			</td>\r\n		</tr>\r\n		<tr>\r\n			<td style=\"width:87px\">\r\n			<p>Does</p>\r\n			</td>\r\n			<td style=\"width:87px\">\r\n			<p>Stela</p>\r\n			</td>\r\n			<td style=\"width:127px\">\r\n			<p>play</p>\r\n			</td>\r\n			<td style=\"width:159px\">\r\n			<p>the violin?</p>\r\n			</td>\r\n		</tr>\r\n		<tr>\r\n			<td style=\"width:87px\">\r\n			<p>Does</p>\r\n			</td>\r\n			<td style=\"width:87px\">\r\n			<p>Maria</p>\r\n			</td>\r\n			<td style=\"width:127px\">\r\n			<p>take</p>\r\n			</td>\r\n			<td style=\"width:159px\">\r\n			<p>the bus to work?</p>\r\n			</td>\r\n		</tr>\r\n		<tr>\r\n			<td style=\"width:87px\">\r\n			<p>Does</p>\r\n			</td>\r\n			<td style=\"width:87px\">\r\n			<p>Matilda</p>\r\n			</td>\r\n			<td style=\"width:127px\">\r\n			<p>stay</p>\r\n			</td>\r\n			<td style=\"width:159px\">\r\n			<p>at day care during the day.</p>\r\n			</td>\r\n		</tr>\r\n		<tr>\r\n			<td style=\"width:87px\">\r\n			<p>Do</p>\r\n			</td>\r\n			<td style=\"width:87px\">\r\n			<p>I</p>\r\n			</td>\r\n			<td style=\"width:127px\">\r\n			<p>read</p>\r\n			</td>\r\n			<td style=\"width:159px\">\r\n			<p>the examples in the explanations?</p>\r\n			</td>\r\n		</tr>\r\n		<tr>\r\n			<td style=\"width:87px\">\r\n			<p>Do</p>\r\n			</td>\r\n			<td style=\"width:87px\">\r\n			<p>you</p>\r\n			</td>\r\n			<td style=\"width:127px\">\r\n			<p>work</p>\r\n			</td>\r\n			<td style=\"width:159px\">\r\n			<p>full time?</p>\r\n			</td>\r\n		</tr>\r\n	</tbody>\r\n</table>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"margin-left:36.0pt\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<ol>\r\n	<li>Simple present and the verb TO BE</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The verb <strong>to be</strong> is an irregular verb. In the simple present, it is conjugated as follows:</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<table border=\"1\" cellpadding=\"0\" cellspacing=\"0\" style=\"width:479px\">\r\n	<tbody>\r\n		<tr>\r\n			<td style=\"width:118px\">\r\n			<p><strong>Pronouns</strong></p>\r\n			</td>\r\n			<td style=\"width:143px\">\r\n			<p><strong>Full form</strong></p>\r\n			</td>\r\n			<td style=\"width:218px\">\r\n			<p><strong>Contracted form</strong></p>\r\n			</td>\r\n		</tr>\r\n		<tr>\r\n			<td style=\"width:118px\">\r\n			<p>I</p>\r\n			</td>\r\n			<td style=\"width:143px\">\r\n			<p>am</p>\r\n			</td>\r\n			<td style=\"width:218px\">\r\n			<p>&rsquo;m</p>\r\n			</td>\r\n		</tr>\r\n		<tr>\r\n			<td style=\"width:118px\">\r\n			<p>you, they, we</p>\r\n			</td>\r\n			<td style=\"width:143px\">\r\n			<p>are</p>\r\n			</td>\r\n			<td style=\"width:218px\">\r\n			<p>&rsquo;re</p>\r\n			</td>\r\n		</tr>\r\n		<tr>\r\n			<td style=\"width:118px\">\r\n			<p>he/she/it</p>\r\n			</td>\r\n			<td style=\"width:143px\">\r\n			<p>is</p>\r\n			</td>\r\n			<td style=\"width:218px\">\r\n			<p>&lsquo;s</p>\r\n			</td>\r\n		</tr>\r\n	</tbody>\r\n</table>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<table border=\"1\" cellpadding=\"0\" cellspacing=\"0\" style=\"width:481px\">\r\n	<tbody>\r\n		<tr>\r\n			<td style=\"width:115px\">\r\n			<p><strong>Pronoun</strong></p>\r\n			</td>\r\n			<td style=\"width:150px\">\r\n			<p><strong>Negative full form</strong></p>\r\n			</td>\r\n			<td style=\"width:216px\">\r\n			<p><strong>Negative contracted form</strong></p>\r\n			</td>\r\n		</tr>\r\n		<tr>\r\n			<td style=\"width:115px\">\r\n			<p>I</p>\r\n			</td>\r\n			<td style=\"width:150px\">\r\n			<p>am not</p>\r\n			</td>\r\n			<td style=\"width:216px\">\r\n			<p>&lsquo;m not</p>\r\n			</td>\r\n		</tr>\r\n		<tr>\r\n			<td style=\"width:115px\">\r\n			<p>you, they, we</p>\r\n			</td>\r\n			<td style=\"width:150px\">\r\n			<p>are not</p>\r\n			</td>\r\n			<td style=\"width:216px\">\r\n			<p>aren&rsquo;t</p>\r\n			</td>\r\n		</tr>\r\n		<tr>\r\n			<td style=\"width:115px\">\r\n			<p>he/she/it</p>\r\n			</td>\r\n			<td style=\"width:150px\">\r\n			<p>is not</p>\r\n			</td>\r\n			<td style=\"width:216px\">\r\n			<p>isn&rsquo;t</p>\r\n			</td>\r\n		</tr>\r\n	</tbody>\r\n</table>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Examples:</p>\r\n\r\n<p><em>Ana <strong>is</strong> one of the computer programmer chiefs.</em></p>\r\n\r\n<p><em>Maria and Lucia <strong>aren&#39;t</strong> married.</em></p>\r\n\r\n<p><em>Stela<strong> is</strong> 16 years old.</em></p>\r\n','PRC','N',1),(160,14,'Atividade 3','<p><strong>Atividade 3</strong></p>\r\n','RPT','N',0),(161,12,'Atividade 4','<p>Our characters in the animation &ldquo;A Day in the Life of Women&rdquo; express a variety of emotions through their voices and facial expressions. Let us review some of them:</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<table border=\"1\" cellpadding=\"0\" cellspacing=\"0\" style=\"width:633px\">\r\n	<tbody>\r\n		<tr>\r\n			<td style=\"width:211px\">\r\n			<p><strong>Facial expression of emotion</strong></p>\r\n			</td>\r\n			<td style=\"width:211px\">\r\n			<p><strong>Name of emotion</strong></p>\r\n			</td>\r\n			<td style=\"width:211px\">\r\n			<p><strong>Adjective</strong></p>\r\n			</td>\r\n		</tr>\r\n		<tr>\r\n			<td style=\"width:211px\">\r\n			<p><img src=\"http://labvirtual.ileel.ufu.br/lab/upload/filemanager/uploads/1.png\" style=\"height:169px; width:302px\" /></p>\r\n			</td>\r\n			<td style=\"width:211px\">\r\n			<p>happiness</p>\r\n			</td>\r\n			<td style=\"width:211px\">\r\n			<p>happy</p>\r\n			</td>\r\n		</tr>\r\n		<tr>\r\n			<td style=\"width:211px\">\r\n			<p><img src=\"http://labvirtual.ileel.ufu.br/lab/upload/filemanager/uploads/2.png\" style=\"height:169px; width:302px\" /></p>\r\n			</td>\r\n			<td style=\"width:211px\">\r\n			<p>fear</p>\r\n			</td>\r\n			<td style=\"width:211px\">\r\n			<p>frightened</p>\r\n			</td>\r\n		</tr>\r\n		<tr>\r\n			<td style=\"height:31px; width:211px\">\r\n			<p><img src=\"http://labvirtual.ileel.ufu.br/lab/upload/filemanager/uploads/3.png\" style=\"height:287px; width:302px\" /></p>\r\n			</td>\r\n			<td style=\"height:31px; width:211px\">\r\n			<p>anger</p>\r\n			</td>\r\n			<td style=\"height:31px; width:211px\">\r\n			<p>angry</p>\r\n			</td>\r\n		</tr>\r\n		<tr>\r\n			<td style=\"width:211px\">\r\n			<p><img src=\"http://labvirtual.ileel.ufu.br/lab/upload/filemanager/uploads/4.png\" style=\"height:457px; width:280px\" /></p>\r\n			</td>\r\n			<td style=\"width:211px\">\r\n			<p>disgust</p>\r\n			</td>\r\n			<td style=\"width:211px\">\r\n			<p>disgusted</p>\r\n			</td>\r\n		</tr>\r\n	</tbody>\r\n</table>\r\n','MUL','N',3),(162,22,'Prática de pronúncia de fonemas de vogais 2','<p>Nesta atividade, vamos continuar a realizar as repeti&ccedil;&otilde;es vogais. Vamos l&aacute;?</p>\r\n','PRN','N',9),(163,12,'Atividade 5','','RPT','N',4),(166,12,'Atividade 6','<p>In our current digital written practices, we also express emotion when we make use of images such as emojis and punctuation marks in messages on apps and social media networks. For example, the expression &ldquo;Happy birthday!&rdquo; can be emphasized by the exclamation mark that follows it, and by a sequence of emojis that some people like to use:</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;&nbsp;<img alt=\"\" src=\"http://labvirtual.ileel.ufu.br/lab/upload/filemanager/uploads/atv6.png\" style=\"height:178px; width:283px\" /></p>\r\n','MUL','N',5),(167,22,'Prática de pronúncia: fonemas de consoantes 1','<p><span style=\"background-color:transparent; color:#000000; font-family:arial; font-size:11pt\">Exercise 1</span></p>\r\n','RPT','N',2),(168,22,'Prática de pronúncia: fonemas de consoantes 2','<p>Exercise 2</p>\r\n','RPT','N',3),(169,22,'Videoaula de fonética e fonologia do inglês ','','','S',6),(170,22,'Videoaula de fonética e fonologia do inglês','','VID','S',9),(171,18,'teste colunas','','REL','N',0),(172,15,'Atividade 5 - Leaving my country','<p><strong><strong>Atividade 5 - Leaving my country</strong></strong></p>\r\n','REL','N',0),(173,15,'Atividade 6','<p>Atividade 6</p>\r\n','RPT','N',0),(174,10,'Atividade 7 - Combine as colunas','<p>Combine a express&atilde;o idiom&aacute;tica com o seu significado.</p>\r\n','REL','N',7),(178,15,'Atividade 7 - Where are you from?','<p><strong><strong>Atividade 7 - Where are you from?</strong></strong></p>\r\n','REL','S',0),(179,8,'Atividade 5 - Análise de Emoção da Voz','<p>An&aacute;lise de Emo&ccedil;&atilde;o da Voz</p>\r\n','EMO','N',5),(180,12,'Atividade 7','','MUL','N',6),(182,10,'Atividade 8 - Praticando os Modais','<p>Escolha a melhor op&ccedil;&atilde;o de verbo modal</p>\r\n','MUL','N',8),(183,8,'Relacionar colunas teste','','REL','S',10),(184,10,'testando colunas','<p>Combine as colunas com as express&otilde;es idiom&aacute;ticas</p>\r\n','REL','S',0),(185,15,'Atividade 7 - Where are you from? ','<p><strong>Atividade 7 - Where are you from?</strong></p>\r\n','REL','S',0),(186,10,'testando colunas','<p>testando</p>\r\n','REL','S',0),(187,10,'mult esc','<p>mult esc</p>\r\n','MUL','S',0),(188,12,'Atividade 8','<p>According to McKinnon (in press)<a href=\"#_ftn1\" name=\"_ftnref1\" title=\"\"><sup><sup>[1]</sup></sup></a>, gaslighting &ldquo;is when a hearer tells a speaker that the speaker&rsquo;s claim isn&rsquo;t that serious, or they&rsquo;re overreacting, or they&rsquo;re being too sensitive, or they&rsquo;re not interpreting events properly. This is often used as a way to discount the speaker&rsquo;s claims&mdash;their testimony.&rdquo;</p>\r\n\r\n<div>&nbsp;\r\n<hr />\r\n<div id=\"ftn1\">\r\n<p><a href=\"#_ftnref1\" name=\"_ftn1\" title=\"\"><sup><sup>[1]</sup></sup></a> MacKinnon, R.: Allies Behaving Badly: Gaslighting as Epistemic Injustice. In Gaile Polhaus Jr., Ian James Kidd, and Jos&eacute; Medina (eds.): Routledge Handbook to Epistemic Injustice. (in press)&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n</div>\r\n</div>\r\n','MUL','N',7),(189,12,'Atividade 9','<p>According to Macmillan&rsquo;s online dictionary, mansplaining occurs &ldquo;<em>when a man explains something to a woman in a way that shows he thinks he knows more about it than she does just because he is a man&rdquo;</em>.</p>\r\n','','S',8),(190,12,'Atividade 10','','MUL','N',9),(191,12,'Atividade 9','<p>According to Macmillan&rsquo;s online dictionary, mansplaining occurs &ldquo;<em>when a man explains something to a woman in a way that shows he thinks he knows more about it than she does just because he is a man&rdquo;</em>.</p>\r\n','PRC','N',8),(192,8,'Atividade 4: Diferentes formulações','<p><em>Quais outras formula&ccedil;&otilde;es poder&iacute;amos dizer para completar os bal&otilde;es e manter o tom amig&aacute;vel das conversas originais das personagens? Para cada lacuna, escolha uma das 03 op&ccedil;&otilde;es propostas e fale-a em seu microfone para obter um feedback. &Agrave;s vezes, mais de uma op&ccedil;&atilde;o &eacute; correta.</em></p>\r\n','MUL','N',0),(193,22,'Prática de pronúncia: fonemas de consoantes 3','<p>Exercise 3</p>\r\n','RPT','N',4),(194,22,'Prática de pronúncia: fonemas de consoantes 4','<p>Exercise 4</p>\r\n','RPT','N',5),(195,22,'Prática de pronúncia: fonemas de consoantes 5','<p>Exercise 5</p>\r\n','RPT','N',6),(196,22,'Prática de pronúncia: fonemas de consoantes 6','<p>Exercise 6</p>\r\n','RPT','N',7),(197,15,'Atividade 7 - Where are you from?','<p><strong>Atividade 7 - Where are you from?</strong></p>\r\n','REL','S',0),(198,15,'Atividade 7 - Where are you from?','<p><strong>Atividade 7 - Where are you from?</strong></p>\r\n','REL','N',0),(199,14,'Atividade 4','<p><strong>Atividade 4</strong></p>\r\n','REL','N',0),(200,22,'Prática de pronúncia de fonemas de vogais 3','','PRN','N',10),(201,22,'Prática de pronúncia de fonemas de vogais 4','<p>Nesta atividade, vamos continuar a realizar as repeti&ccedil;&otilde;es vogais. Vamos l&aacute;?</p>\r\n','PRN','N',11),(202,22,'Atividade 12','<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"background-color:transparent; color:rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family:arial; font-size:11pt\">Once the phonemes are the smallest sound unit in a language that is capable of conveying a distinct meaning, a good way to check if a sound or sound variation is indeed a </span><strong>phoneme</strong><span style=\"background-color:transparent; color:rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family:arial; font-size:11pt\"> in a given language is by contrasting different words with similar sounds. A </span><strong>minimal pair</strong><span style=\"background-color:transparent; color:rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family:arial; font-size:11pt\"> is a pair of words with only one different sound and with different meaning.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"background-color:transparent; color:rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family:arial; font-size:11pt\">Many of the words in activity 1 can be examples of minimal pairs.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<div>&nbsp;</div>\r\n','MUL','N',12),(203,10,'teste','<p>teste</p>\r\n','MUL','S',0),(204,10,'Atividade 3: Combine imagem e palavra','<p>Observe a imagem e escolha a op&ccedil;&atilde;o correspondente.</p>\r\n','MUL','N',3);
